<HEAD>Contract Battle Waged Over Controversial National Event</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Organizers of a rodeo for homosexuals on Friday accused officials of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada-Reno </ORGANIZATION> officials of bowing to public pressure and using a contract dispute to cancel the contest. In August, the university's <ORGANIZATION> Lawlor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Events </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> canceled the contract to rent out its stadium Oct. 21-23 for the international championship gay rodeo, in which top riders from regional gay rodeos compete. `` I think it is just an excuse on the part of <LOCATION> Lawlor </LOCATION> to prevent these types of events from coming to the facility,'' attorney <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumpter </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Washoe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Klasic </PERSON>, general counsel for the university and <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON>, denied the charge, telling the judge, `` It has always been a contract action. This is not a civil rights action.'' On Sept. 1, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rodeo </ORGANIZATION> and the Silver State Gay Rodeo associations sued <ORGANIZATION> UNR </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the events center on its campus. The associations are seeking an injuction from Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Forman </PERSON> to force <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> to rent its stadium for the gay rodeo, which has been advertised for several months throughout the world. <PERSON> Forman </PERSON> said he would rule on the injuction Monday. <PERSON> Klasic </PERSON> told the court the contract was canceled by <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> after Aug. 15 when the gay organization failed to come up with $ 9,000 in pre-payments to cover expenses for security, parking, cleanup and other operation costs. He said <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> became concerned about the organization's ability to pay expenses so a prepayment schedule was orally agreed to in June. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Krambeal </PERSON>, president of the international association, said he only agreed to the demands because he feared <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> otherwise would cancel the event. His organization paid $ 2,263 in prepayments before running out of money. During initial contract talks in October 1987 and when the document was signed in February 1988, <PERSON> Krambeal </PERSON> said he was told expenses would not be due until Oct. 23. <PERSON> Sumpter </PERSON> said the written contract did not call for any prepayments. Instead, it only required that $ 7,300 be paid up front to rent out the stadium, which was done, he said. <PERSON> Sumpter </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> used the financial concern as a way to cause the association to violate its contract because of negative complaints from area residents who protested similar events held in the late 1970s and early 1980s. The prepayment plan was decided only after news leaked that a gay rodeo was returning to <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> and two local business groups told <PERSON> Lawlor </PERSON> officials that previous gay rodeo organizations did n't pay all their bills, he said.
