<HEAD>Guerrillas free five imprisoned comrades, kill hostage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Left-wing guerrillas firing automatic weapons burst into a federal court building in the town of <LOCATION> Buga </LOCATION> Friday and freed five of their comrades being held for trial, police reported. They said a judge's administrative assistant was taken hostage by the gunmen and his body was found with a bullet in the head beside a highway near the town 160 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. Two of the guerrillas freed by the attackers were captured after an hour-long pursuit, the police said. They did not report any other casualties or give further details. In other developments, leftist rebels freed 22 government soldiers and policemen captured in a raid last month and also released two Colombian geologists seized in another attack, the government and military announced. The soldiers and policemen freed Friday had been taken prisoner Aug. 23 by guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Colombian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> during a joint attack on the northwestern town of <LOCATION> Saiza </LOCATION>. A statement from the office of President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcos </PERSON> said a one-day cease-fire had been arranged so the captives could be released in the <LOCATION> Uraba </LOCATION> region, about 300 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. Two of the government troopers had been wounded in the rocket and mortar attack on the police station in <LOCATION> Saiza </LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said in an interview with the radio station <ORGANIZATION> RCN </ORGANIZATION>. He did not list their conditions or elaborate. The two geologists released Thursday were among five who worked with coal companies and were kidnapped Aug. 20 by rebels of another guerrilla group, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, or ELN. Rebels freed the two geologists in an arranged meeting with a group of reporters in the city of <LOCATION> Bucaramanga </LOCATION>, 200 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. An <ORGANIZATION> ELN </ORGANIZATION> communique said the three other geologists would be released soon, but declared the guerrillas would launch an offensive against foreign coal-mining companies. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> state company <ORGANIZATION> Carbacol </ORGANIZATION> are partners in a $ 3 billion surface mine near <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> coast. <ORGANIZATION> ELN </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas have attacked oil pipelines and oil installations operated by <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> state company <ORGANIZATION> Ecopetrol </ORGANIZATION> 46 times this year, according to the government. It placed the damage at $ 300 million. A <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> communique released Friday said 1,174 people have been killed this year in guerrilla attacks and battles between rebels and security forces. It listed the slain as 499 guerrillas, 378 civilians and 297 policemen and soldiers. The ministry has reported 2,037 people were killed last year in fighting involving rebels, government forces and civilians caught in the violence.
