<TEXT>
 A sudden rash of illness affecting hundreds of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> students who ate at a school cafeteria has been blamed on food poisoning, university officials said. More than 220 students had been treated with antibiotics at the school's student health services as of Friday, university spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. Two diabetic students were hospitalized as a precaution, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. All of the students apparently had eaten recently at the Wilkerson Hall cafeteria, school officials said. The cafeteria serves a university complex of five residence halls, which house about 1,500 students. Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Swenson </PERSON>, director of student health services, said food poisoning was the most likely cause of the illnesses, which included stomach cramps, diarrhea and vomiting.
