<HEAD>US, Vietnam To Search for MIA's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A joint U.S.-Vietnamese team soon will begin an on-site investigation into the fate of missing <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> servicemen, focussing on seven cases in which there is evidence the victims were alive when they disappeared. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said Friday the seven are part of the 70 `` most compelling cases'' which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials raised with Vietnamese authorities last year. Other officials said that although the 70 were presumed to be alive when they became separated from their units, all have long since been presumed dead because there is no evidence to prove otherwise. This is the first time the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> have agreed on a joint investigation involving more than one site. Officials from the two countries participated in the excavation of a crash site in search of missing servicemen in November 1985. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, commander of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Joint Casualty Resolution Center, said in a telephone interview Friday from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, `` We're going to do joint investigations of incidents, not just crash sites, but places where people were last thought to be but we do n't know exactly what happened to them. `` I think it's a very significant development,'' he said. `` We think this will be the first of many such joint activities.'' The inspections will be concentrated in an area north of <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> urged the families of missing servicemen to ignore the rumors that will be inevitable during the pending search. `` We have to continue to press for an accounting of each and every one, even though the prospects of finding anyone alive diminish with the passing of time,'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> told a crowd of several hundred at a National POW-MIA Recognition Day ceremony on the steps of the Capitol. All told, more than 1,700 Americans remain unaccounted for in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> since <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military involvement in the country ended 15 years ago. There is no firm evidence that any are alive although officials routinely check out reports of live sightings. The two countries reached agreement on an on-site inspection procedure during a meeting in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> that ended Wednesday, <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. The investigation will involve interviews with villagers and other activities. A 90-day period, beginning Sept. 1, was set aside for carrying out the investigations, <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said, with each one limited to 10 days. After suspending cooperation with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on the MIA issue in August, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> recently agreed to resume discussions on the issue. The suspension was precipitated by <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s unhappiness with the administration's policy of keeping <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> isolated diplomatically and economically until that country withdraws its troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> is one of the few countries with which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not have diplomatic relations. While restoring cooperation on the MIA question, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has not lifted a ban on discussions about a program to permit thousands of former political prisoners to emigrate to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
