<HEAD>Lehman Says His Changes Didn't Weaken Procurement System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> says the changes during his controversial tenure did n't lead to the current <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> investigation of bribery in <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> contracts. `` I am very proud of the achievements made in rebuilding the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> during my tenure. I do not believe the changes that led to that success made the system, by its nature, more susceptible to waste, fraud and abuse,'' he said Friday. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>'s appearance before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was his first major public comment since the ongoing investigation became public three months ago. The investigation concerns allegations of bribes from consultants, many of them former <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> employees, to current <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employees to obtain inside information about contracts. Those details could be crucial to winning multimillion dollar contracts. No charges have yet been filed. A key figure of the investigation is <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, the former assistant <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION> secretary for research and engineering and a close associate of <LOCATION> Lehman </LOCATION> during their <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> tenure. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> resigned and became a high-priced consultant shortly after <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> quit to take a Wall Street job in April 1987. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> was a controversial figure during his six-year tenure, often clashing with lawmakers and other critics of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s naval build-up. That buildup was the key component of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s program of large increases in the Pentagon budget. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> did n't talk about specifics of the investigation and committee members did n't seek those details because they did n't want to harm the probe But he noted the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has more consultants than the other services, chiefly because the service has fewer officers. Some <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> tasks are performed by consultants that in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> would be done by officers, he said. `` Consultants are essential, but we do have too many,'' he added. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> could substantially reduce its reliance on consultants.'' `` I was never comfortable with the dependence on consultants,'' <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> said, adding that his efforts to reduce that dependence were thwarted by unidentified bureaucrats. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> did endorse a pair of reforms proposed after the investigation became public. One would require consultants to register and the other would direct them to disclose all their contracts to prevent conflicts of interest. <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON> strongly defended his running of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, disputing critics who have said the changes he ordered may have fostered a climate which led to the investigation. Those changes include more centralized management and elimination of some layers of bureaucracy. `` With regard to strong centralized policy-making and decentralized execution, I see no way that either principle increases the opportunity for waste, fraud and abuse,'' he said. Overall, said <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>, the Pentagon should be reorganized to give much more authority for daily decisions to lower-level personnel, rather than top officials. He opposed the creation of a single purchasing `` czar,'' a change proposed by some lawmakers. He proposed that the secretary of defense simply make policy, and turn all other major decisions over to the three services. The staff also should be reduced by half, he said.
