<HEAD>House Panel Suggests New Limits On Free Mailings For Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Election-year mass mailings by lawmakers have risen dramatically and prompted leaders of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee to call for new restrictions on how much mail can be sent at taxpayer expense. Four members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, including its Democratic chairman and senior <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> member, said in a letter Friday that increased numbers of taxpayer-paid mailings this year have caused a backlog in their processing and delivery. That could cause some of the mail to arrive at voters' homes during the height of the campaign season in late October, they said. Critics contend that some mailings, particularly newsletters, are little more than government-paid campaign literature intended to promote the re-election of officeholders. Under House rules, members can not send a mass mailing less than 60 days before the date of a primary or general election in which their name appears on the ballot. Mailings must be delivered to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> folding room by that deadline for processing. The lawmakers said that after the cutoff period this month, there were 58 million pieces of mail awaiting processing by the <ORGANIZATION> Publications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distribution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. There were 35.4 million pieces of mail ready for processing at the same point in 1986, 36.7 million in 1984 and 33.3 million in 1982. A temporary second shift of workers was added to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> folding room earlier this year at a cost of nearly $ 500,000, and their employment has been extended through mid-October to help handle the larger volume of mail, the lawmakers said. `` It is essential that additional limitations be considered to prevent this situation from repeating itself to the detriment of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and its members,'' the lawmakers said in their letter. Generally, members are limited to six mass mailings for their districts during a year, but that does not include town meeting notices.
