<HEAD>Conflicting Testimony On Whether Alcoholism Hurt Deaver's Memory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge who will sentence <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> for perjury is pondering sharply conflicting testimony about whether alcoholism impaired the former presidential aide's memory when he gave sworn testimony. Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON>'s doctor during two hospital visits for alcoholism in 1985 and 1986, said the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide likely suffered memory impairment from tranquilizers he took for alcohol withdrawal. But <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarter </PERSON>, an alcoholism expert testifying for the prosecution, said `` motivational reasons rather than neurological reasons'' best explained <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON>'s failures of recollection under oath. Attorneys for <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> offered two days of medical testimony to show that alcoholism should be considered a mitigating factor when the former presidential aide is sentenced for lying when his lobbying was investigated for possible ethics-law violations. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Penfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is scheduled to sentence <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> on Sept. 23. The former deputy White House chief of staff faces a possible five-year sentence and a $ 6,800 fine for each of three perjury counts. <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> was found guilty last year of lying when he said he could n't recall contacting former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration colleagues on behalf of major corporations who paid him six-figure fees for his services. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, head of the alcoholism and drug abuse clinic at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, testified that <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> `` definitely'' suffered memory and judgment impairments during two hospital stays for detoxification. But on cross-examination, <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> admitted to independent counsel <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> that he never tested <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> for memory loss during the hospital stays and meant to say that `` people in that situation have impaired memory and judgment.'' <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> also provided another piece of circumstantial evidence that <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> telephoned then-Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Word </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> was talking on the phone at 5 p.m. June 3, 1985 when he first entered the former presidential aide's room at the hospital, <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said. A log kept by Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s secretary that was produced at the trial showed <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> had called the Cabinet official at precisely that hour. Among other things, <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> was convicted of lying when he told a federal grand jury on June 20, 1986 that `` I do n't recall any government contact I made on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>.'' The defense is trying to show that <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> honestly could n't recall the telephone contact because he was drugged and suffering from alcoholic withdrawal But <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, who testified that <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> later took heavy doses of the tranquilizer Valium to counteract alcohol withdrawal, said the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide was neither drunk nor sedated by a dose of <LOCATION> Librium </LOCATION> he took 30 minutes earlier. The defense countered with Dr. <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> physician who treats alcoholics. She said medical records showed that by 1985 when <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> had resigned from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s staff his alcoholism had reached an advanced stage. Kidney failure that kept <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> from attending <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s second inaugural in January 1985 was `` a classic example'' of the medical complications of alcoholism, she said. It was misdiagnosed as an allergic reaction to blood-pressure medicine because <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> did n't tell doctors he was drinking heavily <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> probably understated his problem when he told <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> and other doctors six months later that he had only recently started drinking more than a fifth of Scotch whisky a day. On appeal, the defense is expected to repeat arguments that improper trial rulings by the judge put <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> at a strategic disadvantage that prevented him from testifying. The defense, confronted with these rulings from the bench, chose to rest its case without calling <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> or any of the medical experts who were prepared to testify.
