<HEAD>Seabrook Finances Now Lone Obstacle To Low-Power License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says the idled <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, reactor will not get a low-power operating license until regulators are convinced the plant's owners are financially stable. But <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> officials, buoyed by a commission vote Friday that removed the only other regulatory obstacle to gaining the license, said they will begin immediately preparing the reactor for low-power testing in anticipation of a license. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> voted 4-0 for a rules `` clarification'' that will allow nuclear plants to receive low-power permits without an emergency siren system in place to alert neighbors within 10 miles of the reactors of an atomic emergency. Commission regulations say financial qualification should not be a consideration for a low-power license, but <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said there are extenuating circumstances in the <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> case. For the first time, he said, <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s finances would be a factor in consideration of a low-power license. `` It's a serious issue,'' <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> told reporters after the hearing. `` We'll be watching closely to see the financial qualification situation at <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Zech </PERSON>'s concerns focused on <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>, a partial <ORGANIZATION> Seabrook </ORGANIZATION> owner which filed for bankruptcy reorganization last January. `` In my judgment, bankruptcy is a special case,'' the chairman said. `` ... We should be satisfied that bankruptcy will not prevent safe, low-power operation.'' <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> communities within <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s 10-mile zone fought successfully to have the emergency sirens removed. State officials led by Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential nominee, believe those coastal towns, with their narrow roads and bulging summer populations, would not be able to evacuate quickly. The new rule takes effect in 30 days. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, president of the reactor's owner, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>, hailed the commission vote as `` another major step forward for <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> blasted the ruling, saying it `` defies logic and brings new meaning to the word irresponsible.'' He derided the commission as the `` Not <ORGANIZATION> Responsible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'' and said it `` is experiencing a meltdown in its thinking process.'' The lone regulatory obstacle remaining for <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s low-power license is a petition filed by plant opponents charging that the reactor's owners are financially unfit to operate the plant. That question was tentatively scheduled for a vote following the siren issue, but was postponed. The idle $ 5.6 billion reactor is losing $ 50 million each month in maintenance and finance costs. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Malsch </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> deputy general counsel, said he hoped the commission would have the issue resolved within a month. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> officials said they were optimistic of a favorable ruling. `` We feel we have proved to the commission that we are financially qualified,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>. If the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> rules that the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> owners are financially fit, the plant would be eligible for a low-power license, which allows it to run tests at 5 percent power. The owners need the 5 percent permit before securing a full-power commercial license, while opponents say low-power testing would contaminate the reactor with radioactive fuel and make a future conversion to a gas-fired plant much more expensive.
