<HEAD>`Truth-in-Contracting' Rules Loosened By Pentagon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Pentagon has slightly relaxed the `` truth-in-contracting'' regulations it imposed after this summer's disclosure of a massive fraud investigation But it refused to drop the rules altogether as industry asked. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> on Friday said its <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Procurement `` has determined that both the Certificate of Contractor Business Ethics and Integrity and the Profit Recapture Clause remain necessary to protect the government's interests ...'' The certification and profit recapture regulations were imposed July 15 against defense contractors named in search warrants obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Fifteen companies are currently subject to the special requirements. The investigation, which became public in June, concerns allegations that defense contractors hired outside consultants to obtain proprietary information on the bids of competing defense companies, and that the consultants may have paid bribes to <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> employees to get such information. The certification clause requires any of the contractors who receive a contract worth at least $ 100,000 to certify that they have not obtained any inside information. The profit recapture regulation specifies the Pentagon can reclaim profits from any company that has obtained sensitive information improperly. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said it was narrowing the application of the certification rule by specifying the written pledge would be required only when a contractor is competing with other firms to start a new project. Under the initial version of the rule, if a contractor was on the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s list, the requirement was imposed regardless of whether the contract was sole-source or competitive, and regardless of whether it was for the start of a project or to expand work awarded to the company earlier. A <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official who asked not to be named said the change was designed to lighten somewhat industry fears that firms could be held accountable now for actions that dated back several years.
