<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> pitched the 14th perfect game in major league baseball's 108-year history, breezing past the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION> 1-0 Friday night. It also was the first no-hitter since the beginning of last season. Six no-hit bids were broken up this season, including one by the <ORGANIZATION> Reds </ORGANIZATION>' Browning. A pitcher achieves a perfect game by allowing no batter to reach base. <PERSON> Browning </PERSON>, a 28-year-old left-hander, struck out seven <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION>. In the ninth, <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> completed the game by getting <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> on a fly ball to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> at the warning track in left field, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Sax </PERSON> on a grounder to shortstop and pinch-hitter <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> on a strikeout to end the game. The last no-hitter was April 15, 1987, by <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nieves </PERSON> against the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orioles </ORGANIZATION> in the American League. The last perfect game was by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Witt </PERSON>, a 1-0 victory over <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on Sept. 30, 1984, also in the American League. The National League's last perfect game was Sept. 9, 1965, by the <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION>' <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Koufax </PERSON> against the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cubs </ORGANIZATION>.
