streets. Officials said about 5,000 people spent Thursday night in shelters. Countless others already have fled the city for towns farther inland, while thousands waited out the hurricane behind boarded or taped doors and windows. `` Our house started flooding, so we called the police and they brought us here,'' said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Crecencia </PERSON> <PERSON> Vazquez </PERSON>, a 45-year-old mother of 10 who sought shelter in a church meeting hall, one of 126 shelters set up in <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>. The refugees, mostly poor families, said they spent all night Thursday in the shelters without food or blankets. `` They closed a lot of stores because too many people were packing in,'' said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON>, 29. `` Most of us did n't get any food.'' The Matamoros airport was closed at midmorning. About 100 miles south of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pesca </LOCATION>, heavy winds and rains pounded the oil port of <LOCATION> Tampico </LOCATION> where 30 ships were anchored. Power was cut in some areas and the airport and coastal highway were closed, according to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tampico </LOCATION>, the local paper. Nearly 1,000 miles away from <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, across the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, much of the <LOCATION> Yucatan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> was in tatters. Glbert caused hundreds of millions of dollars in damages as it rolled across three states of the peninsula destroying 90 per cent of the corn and fruit crops. But tourism officials were optimistic they could put <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cozumel </LOCATION> back in working order in six weeks, in time for the height of the fall and winter season.
