 Armed left-wing rebels burst into a federal court building, freed five jailed comrades and abducted a judge's assistant, who was later found shot to death, police said. They said the guerrillas fired automatic weapons as they entered the building in the town of <LOCATION> Buga </LOCATION>, 160 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. Police said they captured two of the guerrillas freed in the attack after an hourlong chase. The body of the hostage was found beside a highway outside of town, police said. They did not report any other casualties or further elaborate. In other developments, leftist rebels freed 22 government soldiers and policemen captured in a northwestern <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> raid last month and also released two Colombian geologists seized in another attack, the government and military announced. The soldiers and policemen freed Friday had been taken prisoner Aug. 23 by guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Colombian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> during a joint attack on the town of <LOCATION> Saiza </LOCATION>. A statement from President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barcos </PERSON>'s office said a one-day cease-fire had been arranged so the captives could be released in the <LOCATION> Uraba </LOCATION> region, about 300 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. Two of the government troopers had been wounded in the rocket and mortar attack on the police station in <LOCATION> Saiza </LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said in an interview with the radio station <ORGANIZATION> RCN </ORGANIZATION>. He did not elaborate. The two geologists released Thursday were among five who worked with coal companies and were kidnapped Aug. 20 