<HEAD>Hundreds Of Thousands Look For Water, Food and Shelter in Jamaica</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five days after Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> pounded this <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island, life for hundreds of thousands of residents has been reduced to finding clean water, something to eat and a dry place to sleep. A state of emergency was in effect today in disaster areas, where nearly half the nation's 2.3 million people live. At least 26 people died on this island as the storm, which forecasters called the most intense on record, swept across the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Yucatan </LOCATION> peninsula this week before heading for the northern Mexican coast. A half million Jamaicans were left homeless by <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> after it hit the island's east coast, and 80 percent of the country's 500,000 homes were severely damaged or destroyed Prime Minister <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> told a news conference Friday that food stamps would soon be distributed to those most in need. The state-owned <ORGANIZATION> Jamaica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reported that to prevent the spread of disease, the government was trying to move people out of refugee shelters and back to their homes, if the homes had not been destroyed. On Friday, work crews covered roofless government buildings with plastic sheets, replaced snapped utility poles and cleared streets of debris. The <ORGANIZATION> Jamaica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> broadcast health bulletins urging people to boil their water. Children bathed with soap at an open water hydrant in downtown <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, and people filled plastic jugs at a burst water main. Many people stood in long lines to get into grocery stores guarded by helmeted soldiers and dogs. Women and children balanced large water containers on their heads or waited patiently in line to fill cans of cooking kerosene. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> devastated what was already a weak economy with one out of four workers unemployed. The banana and poultry industries were destroyed and tourism, the No. 1 foreign exchange earner, faced an uncertain future. One bright spot was a report by Minister of Mining and Tourism <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> that the main aluminum and bauxite plants received little or no damage. The minerals are among <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s major exports. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>, who estimated total damage from the storm at $ 8 billion, said reconstruction would require `` the largest-scale international assistance we have ever mobilized'' _ from $ 300 million to $ 400 million worth. On Friday, emergency relief supplies had already arrived from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and other countries, and nearly all of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> neighbors pledged assistance. The state-owned <ORGANIZATION> Jamaica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Air </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamaica </PERSON> and other carriers agreed to airlift supplies from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> free of charge. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> invoked emergency powers by declaring much of the island a disaster area Thursday night. He ordered the immediate reopening of gasoline stations and stores that sell vital supplies. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> also imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew to prevent looting. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sent a letter to <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> expressing his and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s `` deepest sympathy for the tragic loss of life'' from the storm, said presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will play an active role in helping <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> rebuild for a bright and prosperous future,'' said the letter. <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> canceled its `` Come Back to <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'' television commercials Thursday, but travel agents in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> reported that many people who had booked tours to the island were still planning to go. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Jamaica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> as saying that damage to `` four or five'' hotels had been reported and they had closed temporarily. Others were operating with limited services, he said. In <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, military ruler Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> issued a brief statement Friday night expressing sympathy with Haitian victims of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>. Ten people drowned when their boat sank Sunday night off the southern coast of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. The government declared a state of emergency in three southern departments. In the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, where the storm caused flooding and widespread damage to crops, five had been reported dead. The <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, which also was in the hurricane's path, reported very minor damage, with 51 homeless out of total population of 23,000. Phones in some areas still out of order Friday and thousands of trees were blown down, but no significant damage was done to buildings.
