<HEAD>Seabrook Officials Start Low-Power Preparations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear plant officials say preparations for low-power testing will begin immediately following a vote by the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to clear a major obstacle toward a long-delayed license. But <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> foes, including <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, declared Friday that the fight to stop the $ 5.6 billion reactor from operating is far from over. `` The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> _ the <ORGANIZATION> Not </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Responsible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> _ is experiencing a meltdown in its thinking process,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential nominee, who has played an important role in stalling <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>. The ruling, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in a prepared statement, `` defies logic and brings new meaning to the word ` irresponsible.''' The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> on Friday voted 4-0 for a rules `` clarification'' that will allow nuclear plants to receive low-power permits without an emergency siren system in place to alert neighbors within 10 miles of the reactors of an atomic emergency. But the commission left open the question of whether <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s owners are financially qualified to conduct the tests <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>, the main owner of <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, filed for bankruptcy reorganization last January. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>, the utility's <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> division, hailed the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> action on the rule change as `` another major step forward for <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> will require about five weeks of preparation before the plant would be ready to begin testing at up to 5 percent power. He estimated that the license could take another four weeks, and that tests could begin two weeks after that. Asked whether <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> was rushing to start testing before the November election since <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is one of the plant's key opponents, he said the timing is `` pure coincidence.'' The lone regulatory obstacle remaining for <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s low-power license is a petition filed by plant opponents charging that the reactor's owners are financially unfit to operate the plant. That question was tentatively scheduled for an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> vote following the siren issue, but was postponed. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> predicted that a final agreement will be in place within several weeks to cover payments being skipped by the owner of the fourth largest <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> share, <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wholesale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. He described that agreement as a permanent arrangement, but under questioning acknowledged that it would provide funding only sometime into 1990. Asked what would happen then, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said, `` If we're not in commercial operation at that point, we'll have to face up to it at that point.'' The idle $ 5.6 billion reactor is losing $ 50 million each month in maintenance and finance costs. To critics who complain that low-power operation could be allowed without warning sirens in place, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said, `` There is no hazard to public safety from low-power testing _ absolutely none.'' But opponents denounced the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> vote as weakening protections to the public. `` The decision again shows the Reagan-Bush administration is so blindly committed to getting <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> on line that public protection does n't matter,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., in a statement `` Its goal is to get this plant plugged in and turned on before Nov. 8 so that no one can turn it off later,'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lando </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> responded that the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s vote `` has nothing to do with the presidential election. ... I think the Nuclear Regulatory Commision is acting within its authority, acting responsibly.'' In his statement, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said the ruling comes at a time when no adequate evacuation plan has been prepared to protect residents near the plant, which lies just north of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> border. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> wo n't submit a plan for <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> communities within 10 miles of <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>. Plant owners have developed their own plan for <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> held a news conference in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and vowed `` to take every action possible including going to the federal court to stop low-power licensing.''
