<FIRST>r a PM-Hurricane-Galveston     09-17 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hurricane-Galveston,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The late A.L. <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON>, a native Texan who later lived in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, was 18 in September 1900 when a hurricane struck <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> just before midnight, killing 6,000 people. It was the worst natural disaster in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. Here's his account of that storm, as written, from his journal of some years later: It was on a Saturday and the wind was blowing from the south, coming in from the Gulf and gradually increasing its velocity as the day wore on. I and one or two of my brothers were cutting red-top cane by hand and standing it in large round shocks. ... The clouds come up about the middle of the morning and got thicker as the hours passed, and about 3:30 in the afternoon I could head a deep low sound of thunder in the southeast and as it slowly come close and closer, the very ground that I stood on would vibrate for long periods. And the wind was increasing, and the clouds looked nearly as black as bellows of coal smoke and -LRB- were -RRB- down close to the tree tops. All birds stopped their singing and no cricket or frog made any sound, just the wind and the continued sound of heavy thunder is all that you could hear. There is a helpless feeling that accompanies any real storm cloud for all of nature's life of low or high cast. ... -LRB- one has -RRB- no idea just how unimportant and small and helpless a storm can make anyone feel, and this storm on that September day is the darkest of my memory. The waves come over the -LRB- 50-foot -RRB- seawalls ... -LRB- and -RRB- all was confusion. You could hear screams for help and the prayers and cries of the drowning above the sound of the thunders and rolling billows of the deep as they come in and over the entire town. In one of the higher buildings ... the third floor held the central telephone switchboard, and the girls on duty stayed until the water come through the windows and then all soon was washed out into the tempest of surging water. Timbers, trees, logs, houses, people, horses, cattle, hogs, dogs and chickens, turkeys and other animals and fowls was all mixed in those waves as they come in and swept back out to sea, carrying in their undercurrent everything that was caught as they boiled up over and down and under, then back to repeat the same action over and over for 12 to 14 hours. There was a Society Ball held on the third floor of a brick building. They danced and sang and prayed, cried and screamed but the music continued until the waves come through the windows and all -LRB- were -RRB- taken. -LRB- When daylight finally came, `` a death-shrouded dawn,'' he was in the water. -RRB- There was a young woman bobbed up right near holding to a heavy timber with one hand and under the other arm she held a baby or a small child, and soon as she could she cried for help. I was near on a timber or timbers that seemed to be the wood ceiling of a large room. I could almost reach out and catch them, but ... as I was about to get a good hold, the bottom fell out of where we was and everything went down and down. But I still stayed with my timbers and when I come to the surface again and got the salt water out of my face and eyes, I looked in every direction, and by the flashes of lightning I saw my young lady again, but she was not close and she did not have that child. ... Very soon there was a mountain of water between she was and me ... and I never seen her any more to know it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> became an oil millionaire in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> but lost his wealth when <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> banks failed during the Great Depression. He and his family moved to <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and he made his living by making saleable items from cactus and clay and by gathering Gila monsters, rattlesnakes and lizards for sale to reptile gardens. He was also known for making archaeological finds, and artifacts from his collection are to be found in the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> museums today. The account of the <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> storm in <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON>'s journal is part of the family archives of his daughter, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Strait </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chandler </LOCATION>, and was made available with her permission.
