<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Peve </PERSON> and two members of the village board have quit in a pig-headed dispute over pork sandwiches and control of a town festival. A third village board member is threatening to resign after a board meeting this week failed to resolve questions about who should monitor the annual Lafayette Reunion Days. `` I'm done. I'm through being called names and having people wave their fists in my face,'' said <PERSON> Mayor </PERSON> <PERSON> Peve </PERSON>. The dispute concerns an ordinance empowering the village board to oversee the activities of a committee that organizes summer festivals. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, president of this year's organizing group, the <ORGANIZATION> Reunion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the three-day festival in August was a success and drew more than 1,500 visitors to the town of 277. But <PERSON> Peve </PERSON> insists the committee needs to be monitored, and some of the loudest squealing concerned the mayor's allegation that the committee slaughtered several hogs and sold pork sandwiches without having the meat properly inspected. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovins </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> said meat products must be inspected before being sold. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, who noted communities commonly slaughter hogs for fairs, said his only mistake was in not asking people to make a donation for the sandwiches instead of buying them. `` This town is supposed to be a community of little helpers, but some members of the board got pigheaded and decided to play God and butt into our business,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORTE MADERA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of items frequently touted for `` safe sex'' made for some unsafe driving conditions. As many as 5,000 condoms still in their packages spilled onto a highway Friday afternoon, but went unclaimed by the owner, according to the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION>. The two fast lanes of the southbound side of Highway 101 were closed for about 30 minutes as three officers and several motorists picked up the condoms, said <ORGANIZATION> CHP </ORGANIZATION> Officer <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Peischke </PERSON>. Officer <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Turnham </PERSON> said some of the people who helped to pick up the hermetically sealed condoms took them home.
