<SECOND>PM-Forest Fires Rdp,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Wet Weekend Expected In Yellowstone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters looked forward to another wet and cool weekend in Yellowstone National Park, but elsewhere across the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> forest fires continued to rage under the whip of shifting winds. The fires that have affected half of the park's 2.2 million acres stayed within containment lines although flames shot through the park on Friday, with temperatures increasing to the mid-60s and steady winds approaching 35 mph, authorities said. Today's forecast called for a chance of light snowshowers this afternoon and temperatures in the 50s. Heavy winds also were expected, but park spokeswoman <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON> <PERSON> Capek </PERSON> said the high humidity and cool temperatures would keep the fires down. Firefighters in Glacier National Park in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> were not as lucky Friday. About 200 firefighters were forced to retreat from a blaze after winds gusting to 40 mph pushed a wall of fire past containment lines. `` It was just an incredible show,'' fire information officer <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Berns </PERSON> said of the 300-feet high flames. Shifting winds pushed the 34,500-acre fire up a drainage along the northeast flank where crews were reconstructing lines that blew out Thursday, <PERSON> Berns </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, officials were throwing all available manpower and equipment at a wilderness fire in the north-central Gospel Hump Wilderness as wildfires continued to burn in most of the state's national forests `` I do n't know if we're over the hump as far as the fire season goes, but we've been saying we're guardedly optimistic,'' said <PERSON> Sandi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sacher </PERSON>, an information officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Boise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Fires that have consumed more than 190,000 acres remained out of control and outside wilderness boundaries in the <LOCATION> Nez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Perce </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Challis </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Salmon </PERSON> national forests, she said. Firefighters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, meanwhile, contained three large fires that have charred more than 70,000 acres. In <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, 30 Canadian firefighters arrived Friday to help battle the flames burning within nearly 1.2 million acres of the 2.2 million-acre park. The `` helitak'' group was the first Canadian crew to arrive on scene since the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> accepted that country's offer to help. The experienced firefighters are a first-attack group, which fights flames from a helicopter, <PERSON> Capek </PERSON> said. This past week, firefighters took advantage of the wet cold weather to strengthen existing lines around fires and extend the lines. By Friday, 50 percent of the 335,500-acre North Fork fire, the most troublesome of the blazes in the park, had been contained. Officials believe the rain and snow that fell in the park had dampened fuels sufficiently so that only seven days of continued dry weather would bring back the tinder-dry conditions that allowed fires to grow by thousands of acres daily, said <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Bungarz </PERSON>, North Fork fire incident commander. Officials predicted they would contain that blaze by mid-October. Military personnel were stationed on either side of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Highway 191, the fire's western edge, to keep it from jumping the road. `` If you put two hot shot crews in competition with each other, it's a situation of two plus two equals five,'' <PERSON> Bungarz </PERSON> said. `` I think the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> will react the same way.'' About 700 Marines from <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pendleton </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> arrived Friday, bringing the military force in the park up to 4,100. Fire information officer <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> said the Marines probably would be out on the fire lines today. In <LOCATION> Oakridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, a $ 5,000 reward was offered for information leading to the arrest and conviction of the person responsible for starting a forest fire burning in the <ORGANIZATION> Willamette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. A fire patrol plane crew and witnesses have given fire investigators solid leads about vehicles seen in the area when the blaze was only about an acre in size, forest officials said. The fire had grown to 7,300 acres Friday, but <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials predicted it would be contained by next week and controlled by the end of the month.
