<SECOND>PM-Kurdistan,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Presents Kurds Who Support Baghdad, Condemn Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSUL, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, trying to counter charges it used poison gas against its Kurdish minority, brought foreign correspondents to the heart of <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION> and paraded Kurds who denounced the rebels and praised <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The local Kurds denied the government used poison gas against them, and scorned the rebels who fled to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> last month. `` If one of them comes, I would drink his blood like water. They are the traitors of our country,'' <PERSON> Naima </PERSON> <PERSON> Khader </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> told reporters Friday in <LOCATION> Sulaymaniyah </LOCATION>. She said her husband died fighting the rebels in 1985. Around her were dozens of other relatives of Kurds killed by insurgents, many holding pictures of their loved ones. The Iraqi government, infuriated by mounting Western charges that it used poison gas to crush Kurdish insurgents, arranged the one-day trip for journalists to show the accusations were baseless. Journalists from the around the world were flown by jetliner Friday from <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> to the oil center of <LOCATION> Kirkuk </LOCATION>. There they boarded Soviet MI-8 helicopters and flew to <LOCATION> Sulaymaniyah </LOCATION>, then on to <LOCATION> Mosul </LOCATION> by dusk. There was also a side trip by bus to meet Kurdish refugees who had accepted an amnesty program in Arbat, near <LOCATION> Sulaymaniyah </LOCATION>. Government officials in green uniforms hovered over each interview and helped translate some Kurdish to Arabic and then to English. They often cut off talks after a few minutes to rush reporters on to the next engagement. At a new cinder block village, a group of Kurds greeted the journalists, chanting: `` With blood and soul we sacrifice ourselves for you <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON>,'' referring to President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>. Officials said the group came `` from dirty villages,'' but several of them said they had moved from the city of <LOCATION> Sulaymaniyeh </LOCATION> to take advantage of free houses. The towns themselves were busy, full of Kurdish men in sashed, baggy trousers and distinctive head scarves. But the view during the helicopter flight from <LOCATION> Sulaymaniyah </LOCATION> appeared to confirm reports that the government is relocating many Kurds from remote villages into new concrete housing complexes and destroying old settlements. Reporters saw several new housing complexes laid out in geometric order near highways on the Kurdish plain. There were few if any villages of the traditional style visible from the air, and dozens appeared demolished. A few were scorched with fire. On Thursday, Defense Minister <PERSON> Adnan </PERSON> <PERSON> Khairallah </PERSON> said villagers were being relocated away from the border for security reasons and also to provide them with improved services. None of the Kurds brought forward by the government accused Iraqi officials of knocking down villages. `` The rebels used to burn the villages and take the families away,'' said <PERSON> Majid </PERSON> <PERSON> Karim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharif </PERSON> in Arbat. Camp officials said more than 4,200 Kurds had returned to the Arbat center, about 56 miles from the border with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, to take advantage of the amnesty announced by the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government last week. The government has said previously that more than 11,500 Kurds have sought amnesty. In a separate development, a spokesman for the Kurdish rebels claimed that 2,400 Kurdish civilians trapped in a mountain ravine were killed in a poison gas attack Aug. 30 by <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> warplanes. Word of the alleged slaughter was delayed because it took the handful of Kurds who survived the attack 10 days to reach southern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and contact rebel officials, the spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Kurdistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> reported in a telephone interview with The Associated Press in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the victims were fleeing an Iraqi military offensive by trekking to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. He claimed the casualties raised the number of Kurds killed by Iraqi chemical weapons since early August to around 4,300. The official also said that <ORGANIZATION> Kurdistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas, battling an estimated 60,000 Iraqi troops pushing into rebel-held mountains in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, killed 140 in a major clash several days ago.
</TEXT>
