<HEAD>Valerie Harper Wins Court Battle Over Firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actress <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was awarded $ 1.85 million and a share of the profits from the show `` Valerie'' by a jury that found the Lorimar production company acted in bad faith in firing her. The jury foreman said the message of Friday's verdict was, `` You just have to treat people fairly.'' Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said she felt `` vindicated, gratified, thrilled'' with the verdict, which her lawyer said could earn the actress up to $ 15 million. `` The truth did prevail,'' she told reporters. `` We won financially. We won morally. I do n't see any loss of any kind.'' The Superior Court jury spent nearly a month hearing evidence and took 4 -LCB- days to reach a complex verdict that required them to answer more than 30 questions. <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which produces the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> series, originally sued <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, claiming she breached her contract by quitting the show. A countersuit by the actress and her husband contended she was wrongfully fired in August 1987. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and individual producers were dropped from that suit during trial. The jury found that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, her husband, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cacciotti </PERSON>, and their company, <ORGANIZATION> AV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION>, had lived up to their contracts with <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON>. But they said <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> acted `` in bad faith, without a reasonable basis or probable cause'' by firing the actress. Jurors believed that <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> witnesses lied when they said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was out to `` submarine the show,'' said the jury foreman, postal worker <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> McDaniels </PERSON>. The firm should not have held a crucial meeting in Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s absence before firing her, he said `` The television business is just like any other business,'' <PERSON> McDaniels </PERSON> said. `` You have good and bad. This verdict does n't condemn the TV industry You just have to treat people fairly.'' The panel awarded the $ 1.85 million in general damages for lost wages, but declined to award punitive damages to Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> and her husband, who was a supervising producer on the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> series. Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> also was granted a 12 -LCB- percent share of adjusted gross profits for the 1987-88 season, including fees for syndication of the show. Her contract would have run through 1991. Her attorney, <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Langberg </PERSON>, said the share of the gross profits could bring the actress $ 10 million to $ 15 million in the long run. <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Engel </PERSON>, expressed relief that punitive damages were not awarded. `` It could have been worse,'' he said, adding that an appeal was unlikely because `` the verdict is so small.'' But <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Brogliatti </PERSON> disagreed. `` We're disappointed in the verdict,'' she said `` And our attorney has advised us there are grounds for an appeal and we are considering it.'' Some of the jurors lined up in the hallway after delivering their verdict to get Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s autograph. At the trial, the company claimed that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was emotionally unstable and menopausal, a position she denounced Friday as `` sexist.'' <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> replaced Miss <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> on the show, which was retitled `` The <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> Family.
