<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> said today that a Chinese-Soviet summit can be held if lower-level meetings bring the two sides closer together on issues such as <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. He also denied that the leadership is split over how to proceed with troubled economic reforms and said that reports of major resistance to reform are groundless. The premier, meeting with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> board of directors and executives, said improved relations with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> were in the interests of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and world peace and would not threaten <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s ties with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the West. It was the most favorable Chinese response yet to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s repeated invitations for a summit meeting to end a quarter-century of estrangement between the communist neighbors. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> renewed the invitation in a speech Friday in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> in which he said he was ready to begin summit preparations without delay. The People's Daily and the official English-language <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s offer without comment. Although <PERSON> Li </PERSON> noted <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s longstanding `` three obstacles'' to a Chinese-Soviet summit, he seemed to play down the differences while emphasizing that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` would like very much to normalize relations.'' The three obstacles are the Soviet troop presence in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the nine-year occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by Soviet-allied <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, and the heavy Soviet troop presence on its border with <LOCATION> China </LO