media.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Solidarity leader today said Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> told members of the independent labor movement that he sees a future for the banned group but refused to promise legalization. <PERSON> Wladyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Frasyniuk </PERSON> described the six-hour meeting he attended Friday, and said the opposition side emerged `` with a feeling of victory.'' At the meeting, Solidarity chairman <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and government officials agreed to hold broad-based talks in mid-October to focus on national problems and the future of Solidarity. `` Our positions got closer. I am satisfied,'' a tired-looking <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said after the meeting at a government guest house outside <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> last month persuaded striking workers to end a wave of walkouts after obtaining the government's agreement to hold talks. He had not met with the government for six years. For the first time Friday, other Solidarity members and representatives of the official trade union alliance OPZZ were brought into talks to prepare for October's discussions. According to <PERSON> Frasyniuk </PERSON>, the leader of a Solidarity chapter in the southwestern city of <LOCATION> Wroclaw </LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> told opposition representatives that he sees a place for Solidarity in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s future but could not take a decision now because his hands are tied Alternate Politburo member <PERSON> Stanislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciosek </PERSON> told the meeting there was strong resistance to the idea of legalizating Solidarity among the police and army, who `` fear this symbol,'' according to <PERSON> Frasyniuk </PERSON>. `` They clearly said, ` Give us time,''' <PERSON> Frasyniuk </PERSON> said. There was no immediate government confirmation of <PERSON> Frasyniuk </PERSON>'s account <PERSON> Frasyniuk </PERSON> told reporters that the union decided to continue talks even without a firm commitment because it did not want to be seen as being the first to break off the process of negotiation. After the meeting, participants had `` a feeling of victory,'' he said. `` You could see that the problem of Solidarity was the dominant one, and nobody directly attacked Solidarity.'' The trade union movement, the first ever permitted in the Soviet bloc, was broken up in 1981 under martial law and later banned. The meeting, the second between <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and communist authorities in two days, was called to set terms for a round-table meeting of groups, including Solidarity, that represent various sectors of Polish society. They are to address major Polish problems, including the future of the outlawed Solidarity and of trade union pluralism. `` Some bitter things were traded,'' said mediator <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Stelmachowski </PERSON>. The recent labor unrest posed the most serious threat to Solidarity since it was crushed in 1981. <PERSON> Stelmachowski </PERSON>, a law professor who has been the go-between in arranging the meetings, reported that no decisions were taken `` but there was some progress.'' In the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, meanwhile, the state-run media softened their hard-line support of the Polish government, saying both officials and protesters are to blame for many of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s problems and that the two should compromise. The daily newspapers <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> carried commentaries Friday suggesting that workers were driven to strike by the government's mishandling of sharp price increases in the spring. <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said trust in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s government has eroded so badly that the leadership may not survive. `` Will the incumbent government stay in power or will it resign? This issue has become a political reality and will be discussed by the Polish parliament,'' wrote <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Runov </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> correspondent for the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. The dispatch appeared in <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION>.
