<HEAD>Republicans Pushing `Training' Wage As Alternative To Kennedy Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 12th graf, Kennedy's bill, to CORRECT figure for 1990 to
$4.15.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republicans are planning to whittle away at Democratic-proposed increases in the $ 3.35 minimum wage for the first time in eight years through a subminimum `` training'' wage _ but not until next week. With many senators taking Friday off to campaign for re-election in their home states, Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, was unwilling to risk a vote on a Democratic measure aimed at killing his proposal for a 80 percent subminimum wage. Under the <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> proposal, employers could pay the `` training'' wage during the first 90 days a worker is on their payroll. Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., the chief author of the mininum wage bill, was ready to vote Friday on his proposal to double the number of student exemptions that employers can now use to pay part-time workers 15 percent below the wage floor _ or $ 2.85 an hour presently <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> called <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s proposal a `` mock training wage,'' saying it would would not give employers any incentive to `` open the door to those who have nothing, who are undereducated and unskilled.'' He said his subminimum training wage advocated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, R-Ind., could `` create hundreds of thousands of new jobs. With presidential and congressional elections just eight weeks away, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other Republicans have softened their opposition to any increase, but have not said how large it should be. In June, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> offered before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> a proposed raise to $ 4 an hour over two years but coupled it with a subminimum training wage. The measure was never voted on. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, campaigning in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, said Friday that a lower training wage, the administration's euphemism for a subminimum rate that it has advocated since 1981, must accompany any increase for him to support it. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> called the Republican proposals a <ORGANIZATION> Trojan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horse </ORGANIZATION>, saying <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s proposal for a $ 4 minimum wage amounts to a 10 percent cut in buying power after taking inflation into account from when <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> took office. `` And from that miserly floor, he proposes a further cut for all new hires,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` Can this be what <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> means when he talks about a kinder, gentler <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>?'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s bill would raise the minimum wage 40 cents an hour in each of the next three years _ to $ 3.75 in 1989; $ 4.15 in 1990 and $ 4.55 in 1991 _ directly benefitting about 15 million workers now paid less than $ 4.50 an hour. Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said he hoped to get a vote on <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>'s different subminimum proposals next Tuesday and a vote on final passage by the end of next House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> will take up and `` likely pass'' it as soon as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> acts.
