<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-Radicals Bjt   09-17 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Radicals, Bjt,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Against Olympics Dwindle As Radicals Lose Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radical students demonstrating against the Olympic Games and the government have seen their support dwindle to a handful of diehards, and most Koreans have rejected their violent extremism. The radical movement has lost ground as hope grows in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> that political reforms will end the nation's long tradition of authoritarian rule and produce an enduring democratic system. Many Koreans, including a growing number of students, say violent anti-government protests are no longer necessary. People are increasingly critical of the radicals. `` Students know the people are against these demonstrations,'' a student leader said. Demonstrations against the Olympics, which began Saturday, have been small by Korean standards with the turnout dropping each day. Protests have been confined to campuses away from the Olympic venues and many have been peaceful. The government helped to defuse the protests by ordering riot police to avoid clashes if possible and not to use tear gas during the Olympics. Radicals marching out of colleges for violent protests several times found no police waiting to confront them and ended up dispersing in confusion. But violence has not disappeared completely. Protesting radicals hurled firebombs at runners escorting the Olympic torch to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> last week but failed to stop it. On Saturday, riot police beat radical students who staged an anti-Olympic protest in the heart of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. About 20 protesters were arrested. Student leaders say the Olympics should have been shared with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to help reunite the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. They claimed the Games were being used to keep the two Koreas divided. `` We must oppose single-host Olympics which prolong dictatorship and perpetuate nation division,'' said a student leader, who like other radicals spoke on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> boycotted the Olympics after its demand to co-host the Games was rejected. The peninsula was divided in 1945. The radicals hoped to use the Games to continue anti-government protests by claiming they were being used to cement authoritarian rule. Radicals say President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>'s government is a front for military rule and insist there have been no political reforms. `` The Olympics are being used to cement the fascist regime,'' one student leader told a recent demonstration. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, a former general who took office in February, introduced broad reforms and most forms of political activity are now legal after years of repression. Even the main opposition parties agree that <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> is making an effort to build democracy. The changing political climate began to erode support for the radical movement this year. Once the spearhead for political change in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the movement began losing many students because they no longer saw the need for violent protests. The departure of moderate students enabled leftist hardliners to take control of the student groups. The hardliners have attempted to compensate for their smaller numbers with more violent tactics. But the call for anti-Olympic protests has attracted little support. Top opposition leader <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dae-jung </PERSON> said even the radical leaders realize that the great majority of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> want the Games to be a success. Koreans see the Olympics as a way to put the country in the front rank of nations. `` The students know they will not be supported by our people,'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> said in an interview. Onlookers have jeered protesting radicals at several demonstrations, criticizing them for ruining <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s image at a time when world attention was focused on the country. `` Go home. You are shaming our nation,'' screamed an angry old man at protesters at one demonstration. While the radicals have lost support, political observers say they can not be ignored because of their willingness to use violence. A change in the political situation or loss of confidence in the government could revive the radicals' support, they add. Radicals form less than 10 percent of about 1 million college students. Other students may like some of the radicals' ideas, but reject their violent tactics. The radicals come from all social and economic backgrounds. Children of senior officials and military officers join children of workers and poor farmers in campus groups, united by a common idealism and anger over years of oppressive rule. The radicals say they are fighting for creation of an idealistic `` society of the masses'' with students, workers and peasants uniting to end oppression, poverty and exploitation. But the radicals often are vague about their goals. `` We feel in our hearts that something must be done now. People just talk and the government uses that to continue its rule. We must act to force change,'' said one leader.
</TEXT>
