<SECOND>AM-Korea,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Demonstrate Against Olympics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea-Radicals, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot police Saturday dispersed and beat radical students who staged an anti-Olympic protest in the heart of the capital on the opening day of the Olympics. About 20 protesters were arrested. Students later held a rally at <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the north of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and burned an effigy painted with an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag in the shape of a nuclear bomb. `` Oppose dictator's Olympics,'' students chanted at both protests. About 200 students shouting anti-Olympic slogans tried to march through <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s main shopping district towards Myongdong Cathedral to protest the opening of the Games. The brief protest was held about 10 miles from the Olympic venues. Scores of riot police charged the march after it had gone about 150 yards. Police roughly dispersed the protesters. Riot police punched and kicked protesters and arrested about 20 who were forced into a bus and taken away. Others protesters fled as police chased them. It was the first protest staged in the city center in several weeks. Protesters did not attempt to fight police. Nearly 10,000 Olympic athletes from 160 countries opened the biggest athletic show on earth Saturday under a massive security blanket and the jealous glare of communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. A colorful, 3 -LCB- - hour spectacle, mixing ancient Korean rituals with space-age technology, kicked off 16 days of athletic competition at the Summer Games The Games will produce the first all-out East-West gold rush since the 1976 Games in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>. Later Saturday, about 300 students staged an anti-American protest at <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. They denounced the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> governments and demanded the Olympics be shared with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` Yankee go home,'' students shouted as they shot their fists into the air. About 400 riot police kept watch outside the school, but did not intervene and students dispersed without a confrontation. Radical students have staged many protests against the Olympics and the government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo. The radicals are demanding the Olympics be shared with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to help unify the two Koreas which were divided at the end of World War II in 1945 and which fought the 1950-1953 Korean War <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> boycotted the Olympics after its demand to co-host the Games was turned down by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The radicals contend the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> helps to enforce the partition of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. Radicals demand the expulsion of the 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based in the nation under a mutual defense treaty.
