<FIRST>r a AM-CentenaryCollege     09-17 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Centenary College,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Male Students Adjusting To Life At Former Women's College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE E. SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKETTSTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attending a school where the ratio of women to men is 63-to-1 may seem like heaven to some young men, but for the first seven full-time male students admitted to <ORGANIZATION> Centenary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 78 years, it can be a little strange. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, a 21-year-old junior from <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Olive </LOCATION>, acknowledged that he was `` a little uncomfortable with all girls in class'' but said he was able to adjust by the time he attended his second class after school opened Sept. 7. <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, a psychology and elementary education major, recalls how a female student saw him standing outside a classroom and mistook him for the professor. `` Most of the girls are friendly. It seems like they know me more than I know them,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON>, 21, a freshman business major. <PERSON> West </PERSON> said his decision to attend the school was supported by all his friends _ except his girlfriend, who is a sophomore. `` She's not too happy about my going here,'' <PERSON> West </PERSON> said. West does n't expect to be distracted by his female counterparts, or at least `` not so much on my part but on the girls' part because I'm the new element.'' Centenary College was founded in this northwestern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> town as a coeducational preparatory school in 1867. Admission was limited to girls in 1910 and Centenary became a women's junior college in 1940. The four-year college was formed in 1976, and men were allowed to enroll only in the Continuing Education Division, consisting mainly of night classes. In April, the trustees decided to admit male students full time. <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Prisco </PERSON>, vice president for academic affairs and dean of the college, said the board decided it was `` the right time and the right circumstances'' to admit men full time. She said the school responded to the success of the continuing education division and the fact that male students were requesting admission to full-time programs. `` We felt very strongly that we were operating from a foundation of constraints and that it was the time to go coeducational,'' she said. `` It certainly broadens the perspective of the classes,'' Ms. <PERSON> Prisco </PERSON> said. `` The teaching challenge, I think, becomes greater ... the richness of discussion in class becomes greater ... it brings a whole new perspective. `` However, it does n't mean that we are going to forsake our mission of providing a strong education for women. I do n't think we have to give up one for the other.'' Total enrollment is about 450 students. There were 192 incoming students in 1987, down from 235 in 1986 and 261 in 1985, according to admissions department statistics. Adding male minds to the campus will not precipitate changes in the curriculum, Ms. <PERSON> Prisco </PERSON> said. `` I think we have strong academic programs and I think that's why we have the seven male students ... because they've realized our programs are strong,'' she said All seven are commuters, but dormitory space for men will be available in 1989, Ms. <PERSON> Prisco </PERSON> said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stowe </PERSON>, 23, a transfer student who lives within walking distance, said he decided to attend Centenary because it is a small, private school. `` I enjoy the campus and it's terribly convenient for me,'' he said. `` It's been a really neat experience for me ... but it is a little strange walking into a room full of girls and not seeing another guy there.'' <PERSON> Stowe </PERSON>'s girlfriend also is not too happy with his choice of academic institutions. `` She's not pleased a bit but she's getting over that,'' he said.
