<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli troops killed one Palestinian and wounded 24 in the occupied lands today, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> sources said, as residents observed a general strike to mark a massacre of Palestinians in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> six years ago. Today also was the 10th anniversary of the signing of the Camp David accords which called for Palestinian self-rule in the occupied lands and paved the way for the Israeli-Egyptian peace treaty of March 1979. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> issued a statement on the accords saying: `` These agreements created a turning point in the history of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. They proved that it's possible to achieve peace between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and its neighbors, that the hatred which prevailed is not eternal.'' <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> marked the anniversary by once again blaming `` Israeli intransigence'' for the accords' failure to give the Palestinians in the occupied lands a voice in ruling themselves. But except for the bitterly worded statement by <PERSON> Butros </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghali </PERSON>, minister of state for foreign affairs, the anniversary passed largely unnoticed in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. Underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising called for the general strike to mark the massacre of hundreds of Palestinians in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Sabra </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Chatilla </LOCATION> refugee camps by Israeli-backed Christian militiamen in September 1982. The strike turned violent in several towns and villages. In <LOCATION> Jenin </LOCATION>, dozens of <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> blocked the road with stones and burning tires and threw rocks at passing military vehicles, an Arab reporter said. Troops opened fire with rubber bullets and tear gas. When the rioters failed to disperse, the soldiers opened fire with real bullets, killing 18-year-old <PERSON> Emad </PERSON> <PERSON> Arkawi </PERSON>. A military spokesman confirmed a dead Palestinian was brought to the hospital but said the army was investigating the circumstances. <PERSON> Arkawi </PERSON> was the 267th Palestinian to die since the intefadeh, Arabic for uprising, began nine months ago. Six Israelis have also been killed. Arab reporters said three Palestinians between the ages of 17 and 20, including one woman, were wounded in the incident. Another 21 Palestinians were wounded, at least one critically, in clashes with troops in other parts of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The army said it was investigating the reports. The general strike was fully observed throughout the occupied territories. In <LOCATION> Jenin </LOCATION>, Palestinians painted graffiti in Arabic and <LOCATION> Hebrew </LOCATION> saying: `` Death to the Jews,'' and `` The End Is Near.'' It was the first time Arab insurgents have painted graffiti in Hebrew. <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags, outlawed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, flew from the homes of many <LOCATION> Jenin </LOCATION> residents. In all the cities of the occupied territories, workers stayed away from their jobs, transportation ground to a halt and the streets were deserted. In <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags were hoisted on electricity wires and protesters burned tires. Protesters littered the highway linking <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yunis </PERSON> with nails to prevent cars from traveling.
