<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The newly renovated boyhood home of President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> opened to the public Saturday and the federal official who oversaw the completion of the 19-year project was delighted. `` I'm very excited. I feel like we've really done something important,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Kesselman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> superintendent for the house. `` It looks great, if I do say so myself.'' The 18-room, three-story house includes five furnished rooms, exhibition rooms and work space for Park Service staff. <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, the only American to serve as both president and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chief justice, was born at the house in 1857. His father, <PERSON> Alphonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, bought the house and its 1.82 acres for $ 10,000 in 1851, after moving from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and added a wing for more space. The family sold the house in 1899 and auctioned off many of the furnishings. Park Service officials had no original blueprints to guide the restoration. They had only an 1868 photograph of the house, with young <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> in the front yard, to show the home's 19th century appearance. <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, a lawyer who made his national reputation by serving as civil governor of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and later as secretary of war under President <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, was the nation's 27th president, from 1909 to 1913. <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> lost a re-election bid to <PERSON> Woodrow </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and served as chief justice from 1921 to 1930. He died in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in March 1930, a few weeks after resigning from the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZAT