<HEAD>Soviet Press In Rare Critique Of Polish Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Polish leadership must share the blame with strikers and protesters for many of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s problems, the state-run Soviet press said in a rare critique of a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> ally. The daily newspapers <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> suggested in commentaries Friday that Polish workers were driven to strike by the government's mishandling of sharp price increases in the spring. Trust in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s government has eroded so badly that the leadership may not survive, <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Will the incumbent government stay in power or will it resign? This issue has become a political reality and will be discussed by the Polish parliament,'' wrote <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Runov </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> correspondent for the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. His dispatch appeared in <LOCATION> Sovietskaya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rossiya </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said recent unrest should not cause the Polish government to back away from reforms. `` The country has approached a point in the process of socialist renovation and democratic development where it should n't stop. Further steps forward are necessary to overcome dogmatic and sketchy thinking,'' said correspondent <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Toporkov </PERSON>. `` One should compromise, each to the other.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said the strikes and their aftermath are just another step in democratization. `` But at the same time, economic decline is occurring. Progress in reform over the last two or three years has been small and the workers themselves have failed at reform,'' the newspaper said. When protests swept <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> earlier this year, the Soviet media called the strikes `` groundless and harmful both from the political and economic viewpoints.'' Commentaries carried by the papers then also accused Western countries of agitating strikers. The latest wave of strikes in August posed the most serious threat to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s government since it imposed martial law and banned Solidarity in 1981. <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, leader of the independent union federation, agreed to end the strikes after the government agreed to talks on legalizing the movement. `` On Aug. 20, when the strike wave reached its culmination point, it was clearly determined that the workers' protest in major cases is resistance to the failed economic policy conducted recently,'' <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said. The Polish government this year raised prices 42 percent, a move officials said was necessary to balance goods with the money supply. Thousands of workers struck in protest and another wave of strikes began in August. <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s council of ministers was given extraordinary power to push through economic reforms, but `` it has n't given any tangible results.'' <PERSON> Runov </PERSON> said the government has responded with immediate measures to speed the country's economic reform program, but `` a problem of trust in the government is still an open one.''
