<HEAD>Bentsen Says Reagan Democrats Returning To Their Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, finishing a four-day Southern campaign swing, declared Saturday that Democrats who voted for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1980 and 1984 are `` coming back in droves.'' The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator told an enthusiastic, partisan audience in a small college auditorium that his ticket represented `` the difference between performance and promise. It's a message we understand here in the South.'' `` I've spent a lot of time in the last month going around visiting ... Democrats that have voted for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>,'' he said. `` And I've gone to them and said, ` Come home' ... and they're coming back in droves.'' Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had failed in his role as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s appointee to lead the fight against drug imports in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said `` And now <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants a promotion,'' he said, drawing laughter from the crowd. `` And he wants to pass the torch of failure on to the junior senator from <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> spoke in front of a huge <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag, behind a collection of nautical items including a ship's wheel and lobster traps. On the stage with him was Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., with whom <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has gone quail hunting in the past `` We're opening <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> season a little early this year,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, repeating one of his favorite lines. In this conservative area of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> panhandle, near two major military installations, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> tried to underline what he said was a commitment to a strong defense by Democratic nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` Our message to the new South, our message to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, is strength and stability for national defense,'' he said. `` We support a strong nuclear deterrent. We support the triad, powerful reliable strategic weapons on the land, in the air and under the sea,'' he said. He did not mention <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' opposition to two programs for modernizing the land-based leg of the triad, the MX and Midgetman missiles. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> himself has supported both of those programs. <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> described <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as `` the third senator from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'' for all the work he's done for the state. But even enthusiastic supporters in the audience doubted the panhandle would go for the ticket. `` You're in the middle of the redneck <LOCATION> Riviera </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, who was the area's lone <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> delegate to the Democratic National Convention. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, Democratic chairman of nearby <LOCATION> Okaloosa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took the area 65 percent to 35 percent last time. `` The comparison with four years ago is like night and day,'' he said. `` We've got a fighting chance at even this time,'' he said. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Saturday afternoon to attend to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> business on Monday.
