 A book publisher bought land for a new headquarters in April while planning to publish a booklet predicting the beginning of the end of the world would occur in September. <PERSON> Norvell </PERSON> <PERSON> Olive </PERSON>, 47, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, spent $ 114,000 for the land as he arranged to publish the booklet, `` 88 Reasons Why the Rapture Will Happen in 1988.'' The booklet, written by <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Whisenant </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, predicted that <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> would `` rapture the church'' and believers would be taken up to heaven during the Jewish new year. He initially said the ` rapture' would occur by sunset Tuesday but later revised it to Wednesday morning. <PERSON> Whisenant </PERSON>, a retired engineer and self-taught Bible student, also said there would be seven years of plague, famine and nuclear war before <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>'s Second Coming. <PERSON> Olive </PERSON> said he went ahead with the purchase of the 3.13 acres of land in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> because negotiations had taken a long time. `` We had had a contract on the property for a year,'' <PERSON> Olive </PERSON> said. He said the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> would disperse profits from the booklet if the predictions in it do not come true by the end of the year. In a news release, the society did not say how the profits would be dispersed, and telephone calls to the society's officer were not answered Saturday. The organization estimated net proceeds at between $ 200,000 and $ 300,000. The society, a non-profit corporation Olive founded in 1979, said it has distributed more than 2 million copies of the booklet but more than 1 million books were given away free. The booklet, priced at 30 cents to $ 2 each, cost 15 cents to produce and is now out of print. `` The book has created a sweeping revival across the country,'' the news release said. `` It is estimated that up to 100,000 people may have made new confessions of faith.'' Orders for the booklet are still coming in but wo n't be filled, <PERSON> Olive </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Nashville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banner </ORGANIZATION> reported Saturday that <PERSON> Olive </PERSON> awaited the rapture on a 68-foot luxury houseboat on nearby <LOCATION> Percy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Priest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>. `` Yes, I live comfortably,'' he said. `` The Lord has helped me to live comfortably.''
