<HEAD>Evacuees Head Home As Storm Abates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Gracia in 3rd graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Broken trees and traffic lights littered city streets Saturday, but many residents were just happy to have homes to return to. More than 5,000 people left shelters around town early Saturday after the main force of Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> passed through <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> about 100 miles to the south. `` I'm kind of glad to be back home. I did n't know what I was going to find. My house is 80 years old and I thought it was going to be blown away but it was n't,'' said <PERSON> Odilon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gracia </PERSON>, 75. He said he waited out the storm at an elementary school with a leaking roof and wet floors. `` I feel a little better in my house than at that school,'' he said. While the shelters emptied, the city grew congested. Restaurants and food stores closed for two days opened their doors again. Cars lined up at gas stations. Residents pried protective plywood from windows and doors and mopped up water that had leaked in. Others cut up fallen trees and hauled them away. Despite wind still gusting at more that 30 mph Saturday, work crews were out picking up dangling traffic lights and downed power lines that caused some temporary outages Friday. Southern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> was spared the 120 mph wind that whirled around the eye of <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, but was battered by rain, high wind and tornadoes spun off by the system. `` I thought it was going to be worse, but thank God it was n't,'' said <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Zapata </PERSON>, 40, while she and her family picked up garbage strewn in their yard by the wind. `` I'm thankful it was n't as hard as it probably could have been or else everything here would have been blown away.'' <PERSON> Rosalinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Delgado </PERSON> and her three children spent the night in a shelter, and were relieved to find their home in good shape. `` I was scared, the children were scared, that we were n't going to have any furniture left when we got back. But everything seems to be OK,'' Ms. <PERSON> Delgado </PERSON> said.
