<HEAD>Gilbert Leaves Grand Isle's Highway Just 100 Feet From Shore</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>'s waves washed away 25 feet of coastline, leaving the highway connecting the island to the mainland in danger if another storm hits the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, an official said Saturday. `` Now the state is really going to have to get into the scene because there is a threat to the highway,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Valence </PERSON>, who ordered the 2,000 inhabitants to evacuate during the storm. Altogether, he said, the resort community lost 100 feet of land from hurricanes <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION>. Now <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Highway 1 is only 100 feet from shore in some places, he said. Grand Isle's losses are only a small part of the coastal erosion in a state which loses more than 50 square miles of coastal wetlands each year. But it's a significant amount for an island about a mile wide and eight miles long facing the open <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> due south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. Other parts of the state apparently escaped <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>'s passage across the Gulf unscathed, aside from minor damage from a tornado Friday in <LOCATION> Slidell </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> will join <LOCATION> Valence </LOCATION> next week to survey the coastal damage to the state's only populated barrier island. <LOCATION> Valence </LOCATION> has been trying raise money to build two stone jetties to stop or at least slow down the erosion. The jetties were a major campaign platform for the new mayor, who took office 75 days ago. Since then, he's had to evacuate the island four times for hurricanes <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, and a tropical st