<FIRST>r a AM-TrailofTears     09-17 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trail of Tears,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Trail Of Tears' Wagon Train Commemorates Indians' Forced March In
1838</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XCLE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A steady rain fell Saturday as a small wagon train departed from Red Clay State Historical Park for <LOCATION> Tahlequah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, to commemorate the 150th anniversary of the infamous `` Trail of Tears.'' `` It's fitting,'' observed <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, the coordinator of the project. `` From what I've read, the first bunch of Cherokees were forced to leave on a day much like this one.'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Golconda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, drove one of the six covered wagons that will make the 1,000-mile journey, scheduled to end in early December. Participants hope to call attention to the federal government's forced removal of the Cherokees from their eastern homelands in 1838. `` I think the blackest chapter of our nation's history began with the Indian Removal Act of 1830 and culminated with the relocation of the Cherokees in 1838,'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. `` The government called it a treaty but what it really amounted to was ... at gunpoint. They were made to leave their homes and walk to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> so the white settlers could have their land.'' According to historical accounts of the trek, the first group of Cherokees, numbering about 1,000, departed Oct. 1, 1838, from <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clay </LOCATION>, their last tribal council ground in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. They were accompanied by federal troops and state militia. In all, 13 groups of Indians made the trek. `` About 4,000 of the Indians, or more than one-third of those who started out from <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> in the fall of 1838, died along the way,'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. `` Yet, there are only two marked graves, in <LOCATION> Hopkinsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, along the entire route of the Trail Of Tears. It's a page of our history that's largely been ignored.'' The wagons that left <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clay </LOCATION> on Saturday were pulled by four mule teams and two teams of horses. A half-dozen riders on horseback also joined the first leg of the trek. Among the riders was <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, a farmer from <LOCATION> Woodbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, who said he first heard of the Trail of Tears as a little boy when he saw it mentioned on a plaque. <PERSON> Woodbury </PERSON> was one of the towns the Indians went through. <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> is the project's <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> coordinator. `` This is an educational project and we'd like for people to come out and walk or ride with us for a while,'' he said. `` In my town, I know, the schoolchildren will be coming down to see the wagon train and learn more about what happened on the Trail of Tears.'' `` We want them to know that the Cherokees were n't savages in loincloths, that they were a civilized people whose land was stolen by the white man.'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said the wagons represent each of the six states the Cherokees went through on their way to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. `` The Cherokees followed a circuitous route through <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, a route that later would be known as the Trail of Tears,'' he said. `` We're going to stay as close to that route as is possible. Prior to embarking, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> read a letter from <PERSON> Wilma </PERSON> <PERSON> Mankiller </PERSON>, the principal chief of the Cherokee Nation at <LOCATION> Tahlequah </LOCATION>. `` Those of you who are taking part in this commemoration of the Cherokee Trail of Tears can not conceive the human misery of those you now honor,'' she wrote. `` The Cherokee people had lived much like their rural southern neighbors. They were a settled, agricultural people with a democratic form of government. The effect of the removal was to thrust the Cherokee people back into the Stone Age.'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, an agricultural adviser, said he expects the trip to take 76 days, or about half as long as it took the Cherokees to get to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. Participants are financing the trip out of their own pockets, except for $ 1,000 donated by the state of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, he said. `` I know we'll run into some problems along the way, but they wo n't be anything compared with the sacrifices the Cherokees had to make,'' he said.
</TEXT>
