<HEAD>Mayor Has Had Hectic Three Months in First Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 First-term Mayor <PERSON> Ygnacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> never wanted to be in the spotlight, but he has had a hectic summer dealing with a store roof collapse that killed 14 and coordinating efforts to prepare for a hurricane. By city charter, the mayor's post is not very powerful, but <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> has taken control of a city where several former top officials were accused of wrongdoing. <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, a 35-year-old certified public accountant who served as a city commissioner in 1979-83, said he stayed out of politics after his first venture because he did n't think it was for him. He returned last year to help manage his native city's administration after it was rocked by scandal `` Although the city charter gives the mayor very little power, the leadership has to be shown regardless of what the charter says,'' said <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, a 6-foot-6 man nicknamed `` Nacho.'' `` You have to assume a leadership role if you are going to lead a city through a crisis.'' On July 7, the roof of the <ORGANIZATION> Amigo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Store </ORGANIZATION> collapsed under the weight of torrential rain, trapping dozens and killing 14 people. <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> took control, coordinating initial rescue efforts and later talking to officials from across the country who offered equipment, food and medical supplies for the victims and their families. <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> learned that the city lacked some heavy equipment and communications gear, but said he was pleased that numerous private companies offered their assistance almost immediately. This past week, while <PERSON> Hurricane </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> moved through the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> toward the <LOCATION> Texas-Mexico </LOCATION> border area, <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> and other city officials prepared for the worst, although the storm ran inland to the south in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The store roof collapse had one effect on the city's preparations for the storm `` What the roof collapse did was give us confidence in our rescue procedures, that we could deal with a disaster as devastating as a hurricane,'' <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said. `` The roof collapse was more reactionary and with the hurricane we did have some lead time and we knew what we wanted to do.''
