<HEAD>Troops Kill Two Palestinians, Wound 27 In Day Of Strikes, Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Palestinians staged a general strike Saturday to mark the sixth anniversary of a <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> refugee camp massacre. Israeli soldiers shot and killed two Palestinians and wounded 27, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports and hospital officials said. The army clamped curfews on 250,000 Palestinians in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and arrested more than 100 alleged Arab ringleaders in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in a nighttime raid aimed at heading off the disturbances. The 1.5 million Arabs of the occupied territories obeyed orders issued by underground leaders to stage a general strike marking the massacre of hundreds of Palestinians in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Sabra </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Chatilla </LOCATION> refugee camps by Israeli-backed Christian militiamen in 1982. In a related development, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> marked the 10th anniversary of the Camp David peace accords by again blaming `` Israeli intransigence'' for the U.S.-brokered plan's failure to give the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> a voice in ruling themselves. <PERSON> Butros </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghali </PERSON>, minister of state for foreign affairs, said in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>: `` <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> had hoped that this anniversary would come at a time when there was peace in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and Palestinians enjoyed the right of self determination. `` But because of Israeli intransigence, and the continuation of its occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> strip, and its continuation of repressive measures which stand against all international laws as well as <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> principles, the Palestinian people still live under tragic circumstances.'' The signing of the two accords, which laid down a framework that led seven months later to the only peace treaty between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and an Arab country, followed 13 days of negotiations at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential retreat at Camp David, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> considers that accord frozen since negotiations among <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> broke down in 1982. <PERSON> Ghali </PERSON>'s statement noted the uprising that began in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> last Dec. 8. He said the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> `` have refused and rebelled against -LRB- <LOCATION> Iraeli </LOCATION> occupation -RRB- in a huge popular uprising.'' Palestinians Saturday stayed away from their jobs and kept indoors except for knots of mostly young protesters who took to the streets to burn tires and stone Israeli forces. Late Friday, the army, bracing for trouble, arrested over 100 Palestinians suspected of organizing demonstrations in <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dahariya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tulkarm </LOCATION> in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, a military spokesman said. But the move did not prevent the most widespread and intense violence in several weeks. In <LOCATION> Jenin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers opened fire after dozens of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> protesters blocked a main road with burning tires and stones and threw rocks at military vehicles, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reporters said. The troops killed 18-year-old <PERSON> Emad </PERSON> <PERSON> Arkawi </PERSON>, Palestinian hospital officials said. Arab reporters said <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops also shot and killed 25-year-old <PERSON> Munjed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarhan </PERSON>, from the village of <LOCATION> Lubban </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sharqiya </LOC