<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high school English class took on a task of epic proportions when they decided to read aloud Homer's epic poems, `` Iliad'' and `` Odyssey.'' It took them 29 straight hours. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Samson </PERSON>'s class at <ORGANIZATION> Columbine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> started at 7 a.m. Thursday and took turns reading every word of the `` Iliad.'' When the students finished a little after 10 p.m., they started on the `` Odyssey,'' completing that work just before noon Friday. The marathon reading session developed after <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> told the 72 students that it took 31 hours for the Greeks to sing `` Iliad.'' Someone wondered how long it would take to read it, and <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> suggested they find out. <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> had Greek food brought in for the reading, and the students made paper Greek shields to add to the ambiance in the classroom. <PERSON> Samson </PERSON> said her students did n't care for Achilles, a Greek warrior and hero in `` Iliad.'' `` He's proud and arrogant, and when he pulls back and wo n't fight, they do n't care for that,'' she said `` One of the students said, ` You know, this Achilles is not a happy camper.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TILFORD, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Massie </PERSON> family has learned to step lightly around the house since moving to the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> in southwestern <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. It seems they have a den of rattlesnakes for neighbors. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ima </PERSON> <PERSON> Massie </PERSON> and their children moved into their rural home in 1976, and ever since they've had periodic encounters with snakes. `` We keep our eyes open all the time,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Massie </PERSON> said. Their first summer, they killed six snakes, she said, including one that coiled up near a cupboard in the house. Through the years, rattlesnakes also have been spotted and killed in the driveway, in grass, even coiled around the mailbox. State officials have inspected the home and determined that a rattlesnake den was within slithering distance of the house, but nobody had been able to find it, Mrs. <PERSON> Massie </PERSON> said. On Thursday, the Massies returned home to find their neighbor, <PERSON> Annette </PERSON> <PERSON> Peldo </PERSON>, had just used her .22 - caliber rifle to shoot a rattlesnake that had been coiled near the Massies' `` The snake had crawled around the corner of the house,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Massie </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Peldo </PERSON> `` went home and got her .22, jumped up on the car and shot at him until she killed him. It was really long, about 2 -LCB- to 3 feet, and really big.''
