<HEAD>Casualties And Damage From Hurricane Gilbert At A Glance</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd item to UPDATE with 200 feared dead in Monterrey.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are reports of casualties and damage caused by Hurricane <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> last week:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TEXAS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of tornadoes spawned by <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> hit southern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> on Saturday, following 14 on Friday. At least two people died Saturday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MEXICO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>, a river surged over its banks Saturday and overturned four buses, and 200 people were feared dead. The storm earlier left 29 people dead on the <LOCATION> Yucatan </LOCATION> peninsula.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JAMAICA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 At least 26 people have been killed and 500,000 left homeless. The government declared a one-month state of emergency along the eastern coast and imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew to prevent looting. Damage was estimated at $ 8 billion.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HAITI</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 At 30 people were killed when <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> swept across the southern peninsula. The military government declared a state of emergency in the three southern departments, where 50 to 60 percent of the agricultural production was destroyed. A famine was predicted in that region within two months.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DOMINICAN REPUBLIC</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> caused flooding and widespread crop damage. Damage to the main electricity relay station blacked out much of <LOCATION> Santo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Domingo </LOCATION>, the capital. Five people were reported dead and 100 families homeless.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HONDURAS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Eight people drowned, 6,000 people were homeless and 27,000 acres of crops were destroyed.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAYMAN ISLANDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Flooding was widespread, with an estimated 5 percent to 10 percent of the houses damaged. Electricity and telephone service was disrupted.
</TEXT>
