<HEAD>Pope Blesses Civil War Victims In Mozambique</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 14th graf, `But life...' to UPDATE
with Pope in Nampula; picks up 15th graf pvs: Some Mozambican...
^By DENNIS REDMONT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRA, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Saturday blessed wheelchair-bound victims of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s 13-year civil war and noted improvements in the Marxist government's relations with the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. On the last portion of a 10-day, five-nation tour of southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the pope flew from the capital, <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Beira </LOCATION>, an <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> city of 300,000 isolated except by air and water because of intense guerrilla activity in the region. <LOCATION> Beira </LOCATION>, the country's second-largest city after <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>, has been plagued by almost daily cuts in electricity and water shortages caused by sabotage from anti-Marxist rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> movement. Protected from a blazing sun by a thatched altar shaped like a native hut, the pope delivered a Mass at the edge of a golf course where the grass had been cut for the first time in 14 years, local officials said. Security surrounding the pope was tight. `` The picture frequently described by missionaries who live with you is not without shadows, due to the prevailing situation of insecurity, which ... generates violence, anxiety and distress, leaving limited space for freedom,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said. The civil war, which began after <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975, has forced about 1 million Mozambicans to flee to neighboring countries. Relief agencies estimate 6 million of <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>'s 14.5 million populace require food aid. At the open-air Mass before 50,000 people, the pope blessed a tractor driver who lost his legs when his vehicle hit a landmine and a young man whose legs were paralyzed after he was hit by bazooka fire in a rebel ambush. Port and rail links from <LOCATION> Beira </LOCATION> reach into landlocked African nations and have been a frequent target of attack by rebels, known by their Portuguese acronym <ORGANIZATION> Renamo </ORGANIZATION>. The Mozambican government has been openly hostile to churches in the past, but now is working to improve strained relations. The government recently returned church-run schools and hospitals that it said were mistakenly confiscated when many such institutions were nationalized. The rector of <LOCATION> Beira </LOCATION> seminary, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Machabo </PERSON>, said the government returned two churches in his area that were being used as a warehouse and a gymnasium. In an apparent reference to anti-church government policies, the pontiff said social ills develop when men begin `` shutting themselves off to God.'' But the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> acknowledged the improvements, saying, `` I would like to recognize also the efforts that are being made at this moment for the difficulties to be overcome.'' Life for <LOCATION> Beira </LOCATION>'s residents remains difficult. Communications are poor, stores lack many basic foods, transportation is difficult and residents almost never travel outside the city for fear of rebel attacks. `` But life is improving,'' says <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> do </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceu </PERSON>, a Portuguese nun who teaches languages at a local school. `` Five years ago a piece of meat was an event, now we have it from time to time.'' Later, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> spoke to about 5,000 people at the airport in the northern city of <LOCATION> Nampula </LOCATION>, where he heard more horror stories about the civil war. The Portuguese archbishop of <LOCATION> Nampula </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Vieira </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinto </PERSON>, said rebels killed 8,000 civilians and plundered about 600 towns in the past five years. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> also met with clergy in <LOCATION> Nampula </LOCATION> before flying back to <LOCATION> Maputo </LOCATION>, where he was scheduled to speak Sunday. Some Mozambican bishops have urged the government to talk with the rebels. But President <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON>'s government has refused to negotiate and has criticized the bishops for advocating talk with `` armed bandits.'' The rebels have been accused of widespread civiian atrocities, a charge they deny. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in an April report, estimated the rebels have killed 100,000 civilians in the last two to three years. The rebels earlier announced a cease-fire during the pope's visit and wished the pontiff a good stay <PERSON> Chissano </PERSON> met the pope last May in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, but the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> appears to be holding off the establishment of diplomatic relations as an incentive to advancing the peace process. <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, ravaged by drought in recent years, receives most of its military assistance from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but increasingly has been making overtures to Western nations. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the largest donor of food aid in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has been providing military training.
