<HEAD>Sandinistas And Rebels To Resume Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sandinista government and U.S.-backed rebels plan to resume talks Monday after a three-month stalemate in their search for an end to seven years of war. Both sides called the planned two-day conference in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> a preliminary step toward reopening the high-level talks that broke off June 9. The left-wing <PERSON> Sandinistas </PERSON> and rebels, known as Contras, signed an accord March 23 to seek a negotiated settlement to the conflict the government says has claimed the lives of 28,000 Nicaraguans. The agreement called on the rebels to lay down their arms in exchange for democratic reforms. Shortly before the talks broke off in June, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> proposed a timetable for disarmament and political reforms. But the Contras rejected the plan, saying it did not go far enough. They insisted on the immediate release of political prisoners, disbanding of the <ORGANIZATION> supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> court </ORGANIZATION> and full democratic guarantees. A March 21 agreement to suspend offensive military operations remains in place but both sides accuse the other of violating the truce. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> issues frequent communiques claiming Contra ambushes of government forces. <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON>, spokesman for the rebels, said recently Sandinista troops attacked Contra positions 93 times in August. Earlier this month the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> proposed preliminary talks in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> to be followed by a conference in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. The Contras initially rejected the suggestion, saying the government had restricted their movements during four earlier talks in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and they would not return to the capital. They also wanted <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s opposition parties to participate in the next round of talks. Last weekm the rebels added a new condition. They demanded the release of more than 40 opposition leaders arrested by police during a demonstration on July 10. <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION> recently proposed Sept. 26 for the next high-level talks to be held in a still-to-be decided location. The Sandinistas maintain the talks should be held in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and that only the government and the Contras take part. Overt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the rebels ended Feb. 29 and the Contras have few bargaining chips left. Over the past four months, most of the rebel forces fled from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> back to base camps inside <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> where they receive non-lethal aid suplied by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Contra sources say only 2,000 fighters remain inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, with more than 9,000 in base camps near the border in eastern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. The rebels, saying the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> still get large amounts of Soviet-supplied war materiel, are seeking renewed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid. Both sides are anxiously awaiting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential elections in November. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> hope for a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> victory by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who opposes more Contra aid, while the Republican contender, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has supported aid to the rebels.
