<HEAD>Apples Ready For Consumption, Maybe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the worst growing seasons in recent memory will mean a smaller-than-usual apple crop in the nation's second-largest apple-producing state, growers said The effects of late spring rain showers just when pollination began and a dry summer is coming into focus even as the state's major apple variety, the <PERSON> McIntosh </PERSON>, is being harvested in orchards across <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> this weekend `` It's too early to tell any numbers, but this year's crop is definitely down,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Peters </PERSON>, a vice president of <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> <PERSON> Brother </PERSON>'s Orchards in <PERSON> Wolcott </PERSON>. Statewide, production this year is estimated to be about 2 million bushels down from last year's 18.8 million bushels, according to industry figures. It's also the smallest apple crop since 1972. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemka </PERSON>, a fruit grower in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Greenbush </LOCATION>, said he was just beginning his harvest, and his crop is looking farily good. But there is usually a 10-day period in which McIntosh apples can be picked, he said, and any extended period of rain would be yet another setback. According to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, a cold front was headed into the state and showers are likely. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, the nation's leading apple producer, growers have largely avoided the drought. A July forecast for the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> fall apple crop calls for total production about one-third less than the record 1987 crop, but that's largely because trees naturally bear less fruit the year after a big crop. The total would be about the same as the 1986 crop.
