<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Kurds     09-17 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Kurds,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims It Resettled Kurds In Modern Villages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAMARNI, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has transformed the face of its northern Kurdish region with battles and bulldozers, and an official said Saturday that residents of hundreds of razed villages were moved to new, more modern towns. The government, which has accused of attacking Kurdish separatist rebels with chemical weapons, flew foreign reporters by helicopter to this devastated village and over much of the region Friday and Saturday. Guides ate grapes growing in one area allegedly attacked by chemical weapons to support the government's denial it used poison gas during its recent offensive against the Kurds. Rebel leaders claim 4,300 Kurds died in Iraqi gas attacks. Many other areas visible from the air have been bulldozed in what officials describe as a plan to concentrate Iraqis throughout the country in towns more easily served with power, water and other amenities. `` We are bringing together the families of the villages'' into new towns of 2,000 to 3,000 people, <PERSON> Namuk </PERSON> <PERSON> Raqib </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorji </PERSON>, the provincial governor, told reporters in <LOCATION> Dihok </LOCATION>, 210 miles south of the Turkish border and 250 miles north of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. `` The villages are isolated and far-flung,'' he said. `` It is very difficult to bring services to people.'' <PERSON> Dihok </PERSON> is one of three governorates in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s Kurdish region, where about 3.5 million Kurds live. `` About 200 small villages in <LOCATION> Dihok </LOCATION> alone'' have been eliminated, the provincial governor, <PERSON> Sorji </PERSON> told reporters. <LOCATION> Bamarni </LOCATION>, 12 miles south of the Turkish border, fell victim to the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> army's massive thrust against Kurdish rebels, who had been supported by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The offensive began shortly after a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in the eight-year-old Iran-Iraq war went into effect on Aug. 20. A bulldozer stood on a hill overlooking the smashed concrete and mud-brick houses. Grape vines still flourished near broken bicycle frames, old shoes and an abandoned baby doll. Fire had scorched the orchard on the town's edge. There were no residents. Iraqi government escorts took reporters to what they identified as the <LOCATION> Balisian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, 95 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Bamarni </LOCATION>. They said it is where the rebels claimed gas attacks occurred, but there was no obvious evidence of that _ and no people either The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and several other western European states have urged the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to dispatch a team to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to investigate charges of poison gas attacks but <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> has refused. On a 90-mile flight from <LOCATION> Sulaymaniyah </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Arbil </LOCATION>, geometric grids of new concrete dwellings rose along highways or on the outskirts of large towns. Western diplomats say <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> appeared to be trying to end decades of simmering rebellion among Kurds by eliminating remote village sanctuaries and putting the general population into more easily controlled centers. But the Dihok governor said the program was `` a general decision'' applied across the country, although outside observers have not noted movements on a similar scale outside the Kurdish region. Tens of thousands of Kurds from villages have fled into <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> during the latest fighting. In another development <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s information minister, <PERSON> Latif </PERSON> <PERSON> Nassayif </PERSON> <PERSON> Jassim </PERSON>, said Saturday <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would `` pay very dearly'' if it attacked targets on the pretext they were chemical weapons plants, the official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. In June 1981, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> carried out what it called a pre-emptive air strike against the French-built reactor west of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> to prevent <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> from developing an atomic bomb.
