 Thousands of people formed a human chain at a nuclear power plant in the Baltic republic of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> on Saturday to protest the facility's threat to the environment, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The official news agency said people from all over <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> locked arms at the <ORGANIZATION> Ignalina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> in the north east of the republic. Fire broke out Sept. 5 in a control cable of the No. 2 reactor, but no radiation was released, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported at the time. During Saturday's demonstration, people cleaned up the area around the plant located near a lake and planted trees, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Some of the protesters were invited to tour the plant. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not give a precise number of demonstrators, saying only that there were thousands, or give their demands. The demonstration was part of a growing environmental campaign in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Soviets are increasingly taking advantage of <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, or openness, to speak out. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself has said the government should pay more attention to preserving the environment and earlier this year created an agency to oversee environmental protection. Concern over the dangers of nuclear power heightened in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and worldwide after the April 26, 1986, explosion at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>. The accident sent a cloud of radioactivity worldwide and killed 31 people. Eight <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators and 20 congressmen sent letters Thur