 Cambodia </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> last month had `` reached certain results.'' He said some disagreements remain on other issues, but `` once there is further agreement the subject of a summit meeting will be placed on the agenda.'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> tried to dispel reports of dissension within <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s political ranks by explaining that all top decisions are made by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION>, which is headed by party chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> and includes <PERSON> Li </PERSON> He said decisions made in the past month to calm consumers and cool off the economy, including a ban on further price increases this year, were made `` under the directorship of General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> and some were proposed by him himself.'' Some Western and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> reports have speculated that <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, who advocates bold policies of introducing market-oriented reforms, is in trouble because of the current serious side-effects of the reforms. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said the reforms, initiated by senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> 10 years ago, will proceed, but there is a need to stabilize an economy battered by a 20-percent inflation rate, rising government deficits and uncontrolled spending on public projects. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> delegation was led by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> board chairman and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> President and General Manager <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON