<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said Friday she hoped the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could resolve their differences and end a deadlock over compensation and other issues in negotiations over <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases. `` Well, they have their position, and we have ours,'' she said of the disagreement. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> made her remarks before Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> offered to give up the Soviet base at <LOCATION> Cam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> closes its six installations in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. She told reporters Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> was trying to narrow differences in his talks with Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, `` so I'm hoping they will.'' The Filipino-U.S. talks are to set compensation and other terms for the final two years of the bases agreement, which expires in 1991. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> refuses to say if she will support extending the agreement. On Thursday, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants to keep the giant <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Subic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> and other installations but Filipino money demands were too high. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is considering moving the bases to Guam or other sites. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> now pays about $ 180 million a year to use the bases. <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> sources have said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> offered to increase the compensation to nearly $ 500 million, including doubling direct bases-related aid to $ 360 million. <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> newspapers say the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> has demanded up to $ 1.2 billion a year, although <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> refuses to confirm that figure. Many Filipinos see the bases as an odious vestige of American rule here, which ended with Philippine independence in 1946. In addition, <PERSON> Manglapus </PERSON> and other officials maintain the bases do not serve Philippine interests because the country does not perceive an external threat. Last week, Deputy Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingles </PERSON> told a meeting of non-aligned nations in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, that the bases may threaten national security by making the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> a target in a future superpower confrontation.
