<FIRST>r i AM-France-TrainCrash     09-17 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Train Crash,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Chain of Circumstances' Behind Deadly June Wreck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A report on a June train crash that killed 57 people said a radio alert from the train hurtling out of control 90 seconds before impact was not relayed over loudspeakers at the station until 30 seconds before it hit. An investigating commission's findings, made public Friday, said the accident at the <LOCATION> Gare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> station was due to a `` chain of circumstances'' implicating both personnel and the complex rules of the state-run train authority. The 36-page report recommended better training for personnel, modification of some equipment and an improved radio network. It stressed the `` unfavorable circumstances'' caused by a passenger who pulled an alarm to automatically stop the suburban train shortly before it was to enter <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> at rush hour June 27. The train restarted, then hurled without breaks into the station, crashing into a standing train about to depart. The report said that from the moment the conductor tried rearming the breaks after the unscheduled stop, a series of technical and human errors took place. The report noted that a radio alert was given just 1 -LCB- minutes before the accident while loudspeakers warned of the impending crash just 30 seconds in advance, leaving passengers on the standing train little time to evacuate. Most of the dead were in the standing train. Transport Minister <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Delebarre </PERSON> said the report had been handed over to the head of the train authority, <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Fournier </PERSON>, for study before a board meeting scheduled for Oct. 26.
