<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> must decide by March 13 whether to regulate benzene emissions from at least nine additional sources, according to a federal judge's ruling The ruling by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> declined, however, to impose a deadline sought by an environmental group for tightening controls on evaporation of gasoline, one source of benzene, from cars. Benzene is a major chemical building block for producing other chemicals. Breathing benzene causes leukemia, according to studies of industrial workers. Though EPA has made decisions about several sources of benzene, and is considering major regulations for some of them, the judge said the Clean Air Act requires the agency to make explicit decisions on benzene emissions from other sources the agency has identified _ plants making ethylene, chlorobenzene, nitrobenzene, linear alkyl benzene and cyclohexane; chemical and refinery waste disposal; industrial solvent usage and the bulk handling and transportation of gasoline. If the agency decides these sources deserve regulation, it must adopt regulations within six months, the judge said in the ruling issued Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> expects to adopt a tightening of auto gasoline evaporation regulations by the end of the year. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON>, attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the plaintiff in the case, said Friday the ruling applied to all hazardous air pollutants over which <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has jurisdiction. `` EPA ca n't just pick one source, regulate it and say, ` That's it,''' <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON> said The sources in question were identified in the 1970s `` but just dropped off the agency's scopes,'' he said. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckart </PERSON>, associate general counsel of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` We have a lot of doubt whether she had jurisdiction to issue the order,'' and for the plaintiff, `` the proper way would have been a petition to use to regulate those sources.'' However, he said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has not decided whether to appeal.
