<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ For Britain, a Legacy of Appeasement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOUGLAS, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With loyalty unshaken by hindsight, <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON>'s aide at the 1938 <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact talks with <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, defends an episode long ranked among the most shameful in British history. `` <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> decided to continue with this peaceful diplomacy in order to try to persuade <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> that war would be a tragedy not only for <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, but for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' Home -LRB- pronounced <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> -RRB- said in an interview as the 50th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact approached. `` He thought that <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> must be sufficiently reasonable to understand that.'' <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> bought peace, but <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> quickly overran all of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and started World War II with his invasion of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1939. <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON>'s successor as prime minister in 1940, sharply assailed his predecessor for signing the <ORGANIZATION> Munich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> died haunted by the words he blurted out to cheering crowds outside No. 10 Downing St. on Sept. 30, 1938, as he brandished the piece of paper he'd brought home that day. `` I believe it is peace in our time.'' Home, who as Sir <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas-Home </PERSON> served as prime minister himself in 1963-64, sticks to a generous judgment of the leader he served as parliamentary private secretary from 1937 to 1940. `` If you are a prime minister leading a democracy and you want the nation to go united into a war, then you've got to carry diplomacy as far as you conceivably can,'' Home said in the interview at his 50-room estate, <LOCATION> Castlemains </LOCATION>. Home, at 85, is still active politically as a member of the unelected House of Lords. Self-effacing and impeccably mannered, Home recalls both the chilling details and the vain hopes of the face-to-face talks with <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> was in a crude and rude and aggressive mood _ a very unattractive character,'' he said. `` But <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> was concerned to get this bit of paper out of him, which he'd drafted that morning himself, saying that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> would settle their differences by peaceful means, so a bit of that short time was taken up with that.'' The rest consisted of allowing <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> to annex the Sudetenland from <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, which the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> overran entirely the following March. Six months later German troops marched into <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> finally declared war on Sept. 3, 1939. <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON>, <PERSON> Home </PERSON> said, never expressed any regrets about the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact, but knew he'd blundered with his `` peace in our time'' remark. `` As soon as he said the words, he knew that he'd made a mistake because it was an unjustifiable claim,'' Home added. `` He'd gone back to Downing Street from the aerodrome. The crowds were enormous. I was inside, we were packed like sardines, and I heard somebody on the staircase say to him, ` Well, <PERSON> Neville </PERSON>, go up to the historic window and say peace in our time.' `` And he turned on whoever it was _ I could n't see who is was _ and said, ` I do n't do that kind of thing,' ... and somebody in the next four or five yards must have said, ` Oh, <PERSON> Neville </PERSON>, look at the crowd, go on, do it.' And that's how it happened.'' Home said the justification for <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> is that it saved a vital year for British air rearmament. `` It could have made all the difference between victory and defeat.'' To <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>, who replaced <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> as prime minister in May 1940, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> `` chose shame'' at <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>. `` We have sustained a defeat without war, the consequences of which will travel far with us along our road,'' he declared in the House of Commons.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 25</NOTE>
