<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ For France, a Symbol of Caution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When Premier <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Daladier </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> 50 years ago after signing the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact with <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> and <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>, he received a delirious hero's welcome In most French eyes he had saved their country and averted war. But today, for many French citizens the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact and the name <PERSON> Daladier </PERSON> are synonymous with appeasement, even cowardice. It also may be one of the reasons why the pacifist movement has never gained much ground in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` To criticize somebody as a `` Munichois'' is an insult,'' said <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Azema </PERSON>, a historian at <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' prestigious Political Science Institute. `` Somebody who lacks courage is called Munichois.'' Yet, at the time, the agreement that gave <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s Sudetenland to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> was approved by 60-65 percent of the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> people, despite <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> military accords with the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> government in force since World War I But the French themselves became the victims of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s ambitions when the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> occupied <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1940 <PERSON> Daladier </PERSON>, then minister of war, was interned by the collaborationist <PERSON> Vichy </PERSON> government. In 1943 he was taken to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and imprisoned until the end of the war. <PERSON> Daladier </PERSON> never recovered politically. He died in 1970, having never again held office. `` Even though his attitude during the war was irreproachable, he never recuperated politically because of <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Azema </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> generation is now in its twilight years. The majority of today's Frenchmen have no firsthand memory of the times, its dangers, its fears, its politics. Nonetheless, <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> remains a strong symbol. `` I have the impression that it rendered the French non-pacifist,'' said <PERSON> Azema </PERSON>, noting stronger movements in other European countries. `` Politically, mentally, pacifism was killed by <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>. No French politician can support a pacifist policy, a pacific policy yes, but not a pacifist policy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 25</NOTE>
