<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ For Italy, An Illusion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IGOR UBOLDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The son of <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> remembers that <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s fascist dictator, like Prime Minister <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, thought the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact of 1938 had saved the world from war `` I remember he came home from <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> and said, ` Peace is safe,''' said <PERSON> Vittorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>, who was 22 when his father went to the <ORGANIZATION> Munich </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Giovanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Spadolini </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> president of today's Italian <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and a professor of contemporary history at the Univeristy of <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION>, said the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> agreement to cede the <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s Sudentenland to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> `` generated negative beliefs within the dictatorships and within the democracies. `` <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> was convinced that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> would never have gone to war to defend the Eastern states,'' said <PERSON> Spadolini </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>, who had taken a role that was unnatural for him, that of the apostle of peace, was convinced of playing a determinant role within the Axis. Above all, <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> contributed to the infusing in him the ... conviction that the British were decadent and faint-hearted and could be provoked without impunity.'' Said <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Bottai </PERSON>, the secretary general of the <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>: `` <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> was also the last conference in which the destiny of other peoples was decided in an abstract, arrogant way. `` Then, people thought they could still solve war and peace with political agreements, now we try to deal with this through the more complex mechanism of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, together with the concept of armaments reduction, which is new and more complex.'' Sen. <PERSON> Gaetano </PERSON> <PERSON> Arfe </PERSON>, a member of the independent left who also is professor of history of parties and political movements at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florence </ORGANIZATION>, said the advent of the atomic bomb marks a great difference between then and now. `` At the time, one could aim for war. Now this is no longer possible. ... The European countries can no longer have autonomous foreign policies. These have to lie within the systems of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Bottai </PERSON> said Italian diplomacy at the time was against an excessive alignment with <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> conference was seen as a chance to widen the dialogue with <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, he said. `` Unfortunately that was an illusion, which lasted for a short time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
