<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Munich Pact _ Bitterness still in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One of a five-story package</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Half a century after the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact dismembered their country, many Czechs still feel they were betrayed by nations they thought were their allies. British, French and Italian leaders joined <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, in September 1938 to sign a pact allowing the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> to swallow the German-speaking Sudetenland. The following year, <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> occupied the remainder of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> as well and the nation no longer existed. `` In the history of nations there are events ... which even decades later bring about strong feelings of patriotism,'' historian <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Anger </PERSON> wrote in his book `` <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> 1938,'' published in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> this past August. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s president in 1938, <PERSON> Edvard </PERSON> <PERSON> Benes </PERSON>, had relied on a treaty with <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the loyalty of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to protect his country from <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s fascism. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> were the country's two main allies on which <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> had modeled its democracy. In a 1947 biography of <PERSON> Benes </PERSON>, <PERSON> Compton </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackenzie </PERSON> wrote: `` What finally broke <PERSON> Benes </PERSON>' heart was the betrayal of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.'' Bitter feelings have lasted long after the end of World War II and the reconstruction of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, including the <ORGANIZATION> Sudetenland </ORGANIZATION>, under <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leadership. <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>, who became the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader in December, said in February that the 1948 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> takeover guaranteed an alliance with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> instead of dependence `` on imperialist states, for which a tragic price was paid after <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>.'' However, many Czechs and Slovaks have felt equally betrayed by their Soviet allies. Many of them are younger people who are bitter about the Soviet-led invasion 30 years later to crush the `` Prague Spring'' of reforms. On the 30th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> Pact in 1968, Czechoslovaks were reeling from the shock of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact invastion Aug. 20-21 that crushed the reform movement of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader at the time. On Aug. 21 of this year, thousands of mostly young Czechoslovaks turned out on <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> to protest the 1968 invasion. An estimated 10,000 demonstrators chanted `` Dubcek'' and demands for truth and freedom. While bitter about <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, Czechoslavaks see the Nazi era as being over and West German visitors today are warmly welcomed in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. `` We usually hate the most those we have loved the most, and vice versa,'' said one long-time political observer who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` Look at the eager welcome given to the thousands of West Germans swarming the streets of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> today. One could almost forget the way they -LRB- Germans -RRB- came to this country 50 years ago.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Sept. 25</NOTE>
