<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday Sept. 19</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Lure of Dividends Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the stock market acts like a bull, many investors concentrate on capital appreciation and all but forget dividends. The reason why is hardly complex, since almost anyone is likely to be attracted to a one-day leap of $ 1 a share vs. a dividend that might amount to less than that for an entire year. But when the market stalls, as it seems now to be doing, interest in dividends returns. Newsletter writers tout high-dividend stocks and brokers offer clients their lists of prospects for dividend increases. When the talk is about dividends, you know the spirit of the marketplace has changed, that it has become calmer, more realistic, more attuned to economic conditions and, most likely, healthier. Smart investors, however, never lose interest in dividend yields, even when others are talking about huge one-day profits and the promoters are talking about a new era and new levels of prosperity. The dividend collectors, however, know that over the long run they sometimes can make more in dividends a bit at a time than others might make _ and lose _ in sharply fluctuating prices. <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, one of the new-breed market researchers who rely on cold, hard, provable data in contrast to the emotions, promotions and shenanigans that predominated from 1982 to 1987, offers this evidence: _ Over the past 38 years, the total return on the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock index has averaged 11.4 percent Of this, 4.6 percent came from dividends, the rest from capital appreciation. _ Reinvestment of dividends over a long period of time can boost an investor's wealth enormously Little dividends become big sums when compounded; that is, when dividends reinvested earn dividends themselves. If you had invested $ 1,000 in the S & amp; P beginning in 1926, and withdrawn all dividends during that time, your investment would have been worth $ 19,366 by the end of 1987. But, had you reinvested all the dividend payments so that they in turn could earn dividends, your portfolio during the same time would have grown to $ 347,956. Such evidence is not new, but it still arrives with a shock on the current market scene, having been scorned for years by a public that believed a stock puchased in the morning should show a gain by afternoon. Dividends can not do that, since seldom are they offered more than once in three months. Moreover, you must pay taxes on dividends, whereas you can defer any tax on capital gains until you sell. There are other reasons, too, why dividends fall out of favor during bull markets, chief of them being the notion that dividend-paying companies are too plodding, too conservative, too slow-growing. But when the marketplace returns to its senses, as it probably has now, the beauty of dividends returns to its proper place in investment philosophies.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday Sept. 19</NOTE>
