<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept 17-18</NOTE>
<HEAD>Toyota Unit Makes Rare Foray By Japanese into US Public Debt
Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bond market, which has proven attractive in recent years for Japanese investors, showed it can be gracious on those rare occasions when it gets a call from a borrower affiliated with a Japanese company. The market provided a warm reception this past week for a $ 200 million issue of three-year notes from <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> finance subsidiary of the Japanese automaker <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The notes, sold in denominations of $ 1,000, were priced to yield 8.826 percent, or a slim 38-hundredths of a percentage point more than <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities with a similar maturity. `` We were very pleased. It went very well and sold out within one hour,'' said <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jahn </PERSON>, vice president for <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Torrance </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. He said while the company has no specific plans for additional offerings, he said he expects to be back. According to the research firm <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the sale was the first straight public debt offering in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 10 years by an affiliate of a Japanese company other than a bank or a concern controlled by the government. The last such issue was the sale a $ 20 million in five-year notes by <ORGANIZATION> Ito-Yokado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese department store company, in June 1978, according to <PERSON> Fran </PERSON> <PERSON> Wissak </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>, which led the underwriters of the issue, said Japanese companies have been deterred from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> debt market because of <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> requirements. But he said he suspects other Japanese companies will be watching the <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> note sale and may be encouraged to try it as well. A wholly-owned subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> makes loans to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Toyota dealers and their customers. It has grown rapidly over the past three years, and counts over $ 3 billion in accounts receivable on its books, according to <PERSON> Jahn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jahn </PERSON> said the company started out raising money in the Euromarkets because they offered ready access and cheaper rates, initially, than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets. But <PERSON> Jahn </PERSON> said as the company's growth accelerated, it found it needed to return to the Euromarket more frequently. Over the past three years, he said <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> raised $ 2 billion in 16 separate offerings and that in recent months, found itself going back to the market with new offerings every six to eight months. `` We realized that we could n't raise all our funds in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It was time for us to enter the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. market.'' <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON> said <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> worked for nine months to come up with documents acceptable to the company and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>. He said a first-time issuer could get into the Euromarkets, on the other hand, in two weeks. Nonetheless, <PERSON> Jahn </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> wanted `` to make sure we have the capability of going into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market'' to accommodate the company's expected growth. `` It is the deepest and most liquid debt market in the world,'' added <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Misteli </PERSON>, assistant treasurer at <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON> said he expects <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> will become one of the most active issuers in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> debt markets within two years, joining a group that included the financing arms of the Big Three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers. He said other Japanese companies may also decide to start borrowing here. The increasing frequency of Japanese acquisitions in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may accelerate that development as Japanese companies look for new sources of funds to help them finance those purchases, he said. `` Now that a major leader among Japanese companies has taken this initial step, other Japanese companies will follow suit,'' he said.
</TEXT>
