 Here are some commodity price trends during the past week: Grain and soybean futures were mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat for September delivery settled Friday at $ 4.03 a bushel, up slightly from $ 4 a week earlier; September corn fell to $ 2.78 -RCB- a bushel from $ 2.85 -RCB-; September oats dropped to $ 2.58 a bushel from $ 2.63; and September soybeans declined to $ 8.47 -LCB- a bushel from $ 8.77 -LCB-. Livestock and meat futures advanced on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. October live cattle rose to 69.95 cents a pound from 69.60 cents; September feeder cattle improved to 79.80 cents a pound from 79.77 cents; October hogs advanced to 37.97 cents a pound from 37.92 cents; and February frozen pork bellies jumped to 50.65 cents a pound from 47.30 cents. Precious metals futures fell sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. October gold skidded to $ 412.90 a troy ounce from $ 423.10; September silver dipped to $ 6.326 a troy ounce from $ 6.440. Energy futures advanced on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. October West Texas Intermediate crude oil rose to $ 14.57 a barrel from $ 14.18; October heating oil rallied to 41.37 cents a gallon from 40.97 cents; and October unleaded gasoline improved to 44.22 cents a gallon from 42.06 cents.
