<HEAD>Oil Futures Decline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices declined in moderate trading as the market shifted its attention from Hurricane Gilbert to the oversupply of oil around the world. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the October contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, settled 33 cents lower at $ 14.57 a 42-gallon barrel Friday compared with Thursday's closing price of $ 14.90 a barrel. Other contract months also settled lower. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery closed down 1.41 cents at 44.22 cents a gallon compared with 45.63 cents a gallon on Thursday. The contract rose more than 3 cents on Wednesday on fears of a hurricane-induced gasoline shortage. The October wholesale heating oil contract fell 1.33 cents a gallon to close at 41.37 cents a gallon, compared with 42.70 cents on Thursday. Analysts said the market opened lower and traded in a narrow range Friday before weakening at the end of the day along with the prospects of a disruption in domestic gasoline and crude oil supplies in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The market had rallied earlier in the week on reports the hurricane was approaching the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> coastline near <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and that many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> refineries had ceased operations. But by Thursday, analysts said the focus shifted to production concerns as threats of a hurricane doing serious damage dissipated. By Friday companies which had evacuated workers from oil platforms announced they were resuming operations. `` Once the hurricane is off the front pages, the market will be back to looking at the supply and demand situation and I do n't think that looks constructive,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Byers </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Reports this week indicated the 13-member <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> had reduced its production last month, from 20 million barrels a day to below 19 million, but still more than the market can absorb, according to That preceded an announcement that the cartel's price monitoring committee would meet Sept. 25 and 26, suggesting that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> might be serious about setting production limits that would strengthen world oil prices. But on Thursday, Iraqi's oil minister slowed the market's upward momentum by announcing his country would not lower its oil output and might raise its production instead. `` That dampens any optimism about what could come out of an <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has refused to abide by its OPEC-assigned quota of 1.5 million barrels a day and is reported to be producing about 2.7 million barrels a day Some observers hoped that after a recent cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> would join with other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations in restraining production.
</TEXT>
