<HEAD>Business Inventories Rise Slowly In Sign Of Economy's Strength</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors who had second thoughts after they bought gold as a hedge against inflation have pushed the price of the precious metal lower. Gold prices continued to tumble Friday, shedding nearly $ 7 a troy ounce. The plunge brought the two-day decline in gold prices to roughly $ 18 an ounce and left gold at its lowest point since March 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quoted gold bullion at $ 411.75 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT. Unlike stocks and bonds, gold does not provide dividends. Its main merit is it keeps its value when paper investments are eroded by inflation. But inflation has been lower than gold investors had expected. `` These people are disappointed and shocked and adding fuel to the fire,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, vice president and bullion dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. `` The more selling that comes in, the more these people are in a panic.'' In other markets Friday, stocks gained some ground and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.87 to 2,098.15. The dollar was mixed and bonds drifted slightly lower in sluggish trading. The government said Friday business inventories rose in July at the slowest rate in 11 months, an indication sales were strong enough to keep goods from piling up on the shelves. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said inventories rose 0.3 percent _ the smallest rise since one of 0.2 percent in August 1987. Economists believe businesses have been intentionally adding to their inventories in a small way to have a buffer for continued strong sales. Business sales fell 0.2 percent in July, but the decline was not considered worrisome because it followed a strong 1.4 percent jump in June. `` When you put June and July together, sales are still growing strongly,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Annable </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
